<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Confrontation on Human Rights Leads to Nowhere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China foiled the United States'
anti-China attempt Tuesday when a "no-action motion" was adopted
at the 56th session of the United Nations Commission on Human
Rights, its ninth victory since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Now the question is: What is the real U.S. intention behind its
repeated attempts against China and other developing countries at
the U.N. human rights sessions?
</P>
<P>
Always posing as a "human rights judge" and concocting
resolutions now and then, the United States wants to seek nothing
but hegemony, interference in other countries' internal affairs,
and imposition of its values, including its human rights views,
upon others -- all in the excuse of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who would not be ordered about by the United States will
be subjected to Washington's punishment, threat of force, or even
the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Brandishing the club of human rights before China, the United
States hates to see a China with political stability, rapid
economic growth and a determination to follow its own path of
development. Therefore, it has used the issue of human rights in
various ways to defame China, make troubles and interfere in its
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
It is a well-known fact that China has consistently respected
universal principles of human rights, dedicating itself to
actively advocating and safeguarding the Chinese people's human
rights and fundamental freedoms. Through long unremitting efforts
by the government, China has achieved remarkable progress in this
regard with its people enjoying more rights and freedoms than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
However, turning a blind eye to this, the United States always
seeks confrontation with China on this issue -- out of nothing but
malice. Besides, with its world-recognized poor performance in
human rights, the United States is not in the position at all to
be a human rights judge for others in this regard.
</P>
<P>
China has been pursuing all along the policy of dialogue and
cooperation on human rights, rejecting any attempt to use the
issue for confrontation. Its just and reasonable stance has won
profound understanding and extensive support across the world.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, some Western countries have chosen not to be
part of the U.S.-orchestrated anti-China attempts as in the past.
Some European Union countries boycotted the anti-China resolution
at the U.N. human rights session in 1997. And thereafter there has
been no EU involvement in any anti-China attempts at the UN Human
Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
The United States will hold its presidential elections this
year. Behind its move to produce the anti-China resolution in
Geneva once again despite its past failures is domestic politics
and political strife between political parties.
</P>
<P>
Changing its strategy, this year Washington used the Falun Gong
cult, an evil organization hated and disdained by Chinese people,
as its weapon of attack. The U.S. has really gone too far to link
the human rights issue with an evil cult which could not be
tolerated by any country. The real intention of the U.S. in doing
so is to interfere in China's internal affair under the pretext of
human rights and turn the U.N. commission meeting room into a
dirty place where American politicians canvass votes for domestic
purposes.
</P>
<P>
The failures of the U.S. in confrontation with China on the
human rights issue clearly indicate that confrontation will
certainly lead to nowhere and it is a healthy trend to seek
dialogue instead of confrontation on the issue. It shows once
again that the U.S. is acting against the current of times.
Naturally, Washington's arbitrary deeds were under fire from
delegates of developing countries to the session. Many delegates
expressed full support for China's stance and blamed the anti-
China resolution as anachronistic. They also criticized the U.S.
for double standard on the human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
At the turn of the century, we advise the U.S. to go with the
trend of the times, give up its Cold War mentality, shift to
dialogue and cooperation and do something that can really promote
the human rights cause. Otherwise, it will not only suffer more
embarrassments, but will also be opposed by all justice-upholding
countries and peoples in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
