<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Victory of Justice -- China Foils U.S. Anti-China Attempt Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The rollcall at the 53 members of
the United Nations Human Rights Commission for once seemed to last
forever, turning the voting process into a contest as heated as
any sports contest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Official delegates to the annual commission session, observers,
representatives of non-governmental organizations and members of
the mass media chalked down and calculated fervently the votes on
scoresheets in front of them.
</P>
<P>
Though a hush befell upon the human rights commission hall
where the secretariat rollcalled the members to cast their votes
on China's "no-action motion" regarding the United States draft
resolution, cheers and sighs rang out from time to time as the
votes in favor of China rallied from behind to surpass the votes
supporting the Americans.
</P>
<P>
When the president of the commission pronounced the final
result, the contest ended with China garnering 22 votes against 18
to the United States with 12 abstentions and one absentee.
</P>
<P>
It was the ninth defeat sustained by the United States-led
western bloc since 1990.
</P>
<P>
There was no draft resolution tabled by the United States or
other countries in 1991 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Though the United States boasted full confidence in voting down
China's "no-action motion" just prior to the voting, the ballot
went to the Chinese side when not more than one third of the
voting process was finished.
</P>
<P>
Sides were taken naturally on occasions like this and the side-
taking was so obvious when most of the developing countries on the
commission supported China on grounds that the U.S. practice of
confronting China on the issue of human rights was simply not the
right way to deal with it. All the developed countries sided with
the Americans.
</P>
<P>
Russia said prior to the ballot that the United States only
tried to politicize the issue of human rights and it pointed out
that political confrontation would lead to nowhere but counter-
reaction.
</P>
<P>
Cuba criticized the United States for its double standards on
dealing with the human rights issue of other nations and its own
and supported China's no-action motion by saying that it was right
in accordance with the U.N. laws of procedure and the motion has
been used time and again by the United States itself and other
western countries in the past.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan regretted the fact that the annual U.N. forum was used
by the politically selective United States as a platform for
political combat.
</P>
<P>
The Sudan said that China has made much progress in protecting
and promoting the economic and social rights of its people that
should have been witnessed by all.
</P>
<P>
With four countries remaining and China leading 20-18, Qatar
added one more supportive vote to China, followed by the
abstention of South Korea. Romania was absent when it was called
upon to vote only to leave Russia to seal off the victory for
China in the very end.
</P>
<P>
Applause broke out immediately after Russia's vote in favor of
China and the president of the commission had to caution with his
little hammer the congratulatory applause and announced the
official result for the fully-packed hall to explode once again
into applause of congratulation and celebration.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from developing countries came to shake hands with
the Chinese delegates and offer congratulatory phrases and all
that voted for China burst into hearty smiles as they concluded
the morning session of Tuesday's commission meeting.
</P>
<P>
"It was a victory of justice," said one delegate from the
Pakistani delegation. When the contest was over, a delegate from
Africa echoed resoundingly: "Justice will as always beat off the
evil." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
