<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Economy Drives Changes: Singapore PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Delivering a keynote speech on southeast Asia's economic
development, Goh said southeast Asia is recovering from the
devastation of the regional financial crisis with the resumption
of the economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"But there remain major challenges ahead," he said. "The
southeast Asian countries are also having to grapple with the New
Economy even as they seek to turn around their traditional sectors.
"
</P>
<P>
Goh pointed out that politics and economics are intertwined,
and managing contradictory currents towards reform, protectionism
and nationalism will be a major political challenge.
</P>
<P>
He said Singapore is preparing for the next phase of the
development and the emergence of the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
The country is making its efforts along four lines, including
deregulating and liberalizing the service sector, deepening and
broadening the capital market, building IT infrastructure, and
fostering a creative and entrepreneurial spirit in the people, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
Singapore must move beyond being a "value adding" economy to
become a "value creation" economy to remain relevant and
competitive in the New Economy, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Earning a living is no longer just about reducing costs, or
finding ways to make incremental improvement to an existing
product or process. It is about harnessing the creativity and
innovation of our people to generate wealth through
entrepreneurial endeavors," he said.
</P>
<P>
In referring to the relations between Singapore and the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region, Goh said the two should
continue as competitors "because that is a sure sign that we are
both alive and kicking."
</P>
<P>
Singapore has always treated Hong Kong as a benchmark for
enterprise, he said, adding that Singapore companies have invested
far in excess of 50 billion HK dollars (6.4 billion U.S. dollars)
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I believe there will always be a certain amount of competitive
tension between us. But we need also to work together," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
