<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahraini PM Ends Visit to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Bahraini Prime Minister Sheikh
Khalifa Bin Sulman Al-Khalifa left here Wednesday evening after a
two-day official visit to Jordan to promote bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the two countries signed three protocols to
consolidate bilateral cooperation in health, culture and science.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to set up a higher joint committee
which will be co-chaired by the two prime ministers to supervise
the implementation of the agreements already signed between the two
countries as part of the efforts to further enhance bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's talks, Khalifa and Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh reviewed the latest developments in the Middle
East peace process, and said that both countries stand for a just,
durable and comprehensive peace in the region on the basis of the
land-for-peace principle and relevant resolutions by the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Khalifa's visit to Jordan is part of the increasing high-level
contacts between the two countries after Jordanian King Abdullah
Bin Hussein and Bahraini Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Isa Al-Khalifa came
to power in February and March 1999, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's ties with the Arab gulf states had been severely
affected by the 1990 Gulf crisis as Amman was believed to side with
Iraq after Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
King Abdullah adopts peace and cooperation as the corner stone
of his foreign policies, and is trying to improve Jordan's
relations with the Arab Gulf states while maintaining a friendly
relations with Iraq, currently the only crude oil supplier to the
kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
