<HEADLINE> 10,000 Somali Refugees Return Home From Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,000 refugees of
Somalia have voluntarily returned home since March from Ethiopia,
the East Ethiopia Refugees and Returnees Affairs Coordination
Office said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The refugees had been residing in Rubaso, Daroro and Kamaboker
refugee camps before they returned their native land, the office
said in Jijiga, capital of Somali State, Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
provided the refugees with a nine-month ration and household
utensils each, branch office head Tsegaye Mihretu said.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were also given transport allowances to reach to
their original birthplaces following their arrival in Somalia, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNHCR official, a total of 90,000 of the
163,000 Somali refugees living in east Ethiopia have so far
voluntarily returned to their homeland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
