<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean White Farmers Invited to Settle in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean white commercial
farmers have been invited to settle in Mozambican central province
of Manica.
</P>
<P>
Manica provincial governor Felicio Zacarias was quoted by
Wednesday's issue of the independent news sheet "Metical" as
saying that negotiations were almost concluded for 150 Zimbabwean
farmers to settle in Manica.
</P>
<P>
But he said the negotiations to settle Zimbabweans in Manica
have been going on for two years, and are not directly related to
the current seizure of commercial farms by Zimbabwean war
veterans.
</P>
<P>
These farmers, he said, will be granted land in Barue district,
which is sparsely populated, and where there is little potential
for land conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Zacarias believed that up to 500,000 hectares could be
available for commercial farming. But the scheme will start with
much smaller amounts with each of the farmers be granted between
200 and 300 hectares.
</P>
<P>
He thought that perhaps 40 Zimbabwean farmers and their
families could be installed in Barue by the start of the next
agricultural year in September.
</P>
<P>
He said that some of these farmers, whom he regarded as
"perhaps the best on the African continent", had their roots in
Africa for three or four generations. "Some of them speak Shona
better than I do", he joked. Shona is the main African language
spoken in Zimbabwe, and the languages spoken in Manica are closely
related to it.
</P>
<P>
Zacarias said the financial aspects of the move from Zimbabwe
to Mozambique were almost settled, with just some insurance
details outstanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
