<HEADLINE> Britain's Blair Resists Calls to Punish Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
on Wednesday rejected calls for moves to suspend Zimbabwe's
commonwealth membership over the farm-seizure crisis there.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions in the House of Commons about situation in
the former British colony, Blair said people in Zimbabwe were
warning against emotional reaction or interference.
</P>
<P>
"It is best we are guided by those with most to lose, not those
commenting from a safe distance," he told the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Stressing it was important that any action Britain took did not
make it worse for the white farmers in Zimbabwe, Blair condemned
the attacks on farms owned by white people, mostly from Britain
originally.
</P>
<P>
"Of course it is a disgraceful situation in Zimbabwe. We
condemn utterly the barbaric attacks on farmers," He said.
</P>
<P>
Blair said Britain was pursuing "every avenue open to us" to
try to stop the attacks, through the Commonwealth, the European
Union and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The government was also in touch with Zimbabwean opposition
leaders and farmers' unions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some parliament members argued that Britain should freeze the
financial assets of Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe or agitate
for the Commonwealth to suspend Zimbabwe in the wake of farm
invasions that have seen a policeman and two white farmers killed
there.
</P>
