<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges to Strengthen U.N. Ability to Protect Civilians in Armed Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Wednesday urged the United Nations security Council
to consider taking further steps towards strengthen the
Organization's ability to protect civilians in armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the open debate of the Security Council on
protection of civilians in armed conflict, Annan once again
recommended that a rapid deployment force be created, which he
thinks as the most far-reaching measure.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in East Timor underscored the importance of having
a more systematic rapid reaction capacity in the United Nations,
Annan told the 15-member Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief also recommended the Security Council make use
of preventive deployment when there has been sufficient warning of
impending attacks or an escalation of conflict.
</P>
<P>
"In February of this year, we successfully concluded such a
mission in the Central African Republic," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the Security Council's willingness to consider the
further establishment of preventive missions, including the
dispatch of monitors and fact-finding mission.
</P>
<P>
A critical element in enhancing the protection of civilian in
armed conflict lies in improving the security of camps for
refugees, the U.N. chief stressed.
</P>
<P>
U.N. agencies and others have taken a number of initiatives in
relation to the security, civilian and humanitarian character of
refugees camps and settlements, he said.
</P>
<P>
In future conflict situations, it may be necessary to consider
temporary security zones and safe corridors for the protection of
civilians, Annan noted.
</P>
<P>
"The open debate of the Security Council bears vivid testimony
to a growing recognition that our first duty in any conflict is to
support the innocent civilian -- who have no part in the fighting,
who have nothing to gain from its persistence, and who have no
choice but to rely on the international community to help them in
their most desperate hour of need, " the U.N. chief added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
