<HEADLINE> Canada Reports 8 Percent Drop in Gasoline Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Gasoline prices have fallen to an
average 66.8 cents (about 0.45 U.S. dollars) a liter in Canada
from their record high at 72.6 cents (about 0.49 U.S. dollars) on
March 21.
</P>
<P>
The 8 percent drop is part of a reversal from a 15-month upward
trend since January of 1999, when the prices were as low as 47.5
cents (about 0.32 U.S. dollars) a liter, the Globe and Mail
newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices have steadily come down after the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries decided to increase production on
March 28.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices have dipped to about 26 U.S. dollars a barrel
from more than 34 dollars in early March.
</P>
<P>
The price alleviation is better than expected than many
analysts, who originally thought that the increased crude oil
production would not turn into noticeable savings at the Canadian
pumps until July or August.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the going-down trend may also be fragile as U.S.
gasoline inventories remain at historic lows, according to the
newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
