<HEADLINE> UK Government To Tackle Distraction Burglary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) - A package of measures to tackle
distraction burglary, often called 'burglary artifice', was
announced by British Crime Minister Charles Clarke Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The plans include a nationwide leaflet drop by the National
Neighborhood Watch Association (NNWA) and the creation of 20 pilot
schemes across England and Wales to help identify ways to tackle
this crime.
</P>
<P>
Distraction burglaries claim over 16000 victims every year in
Britain but the true figure is believed to be much higher because
many people do not report the burglary.
</P>
<P>
Home Office said that one of the reasons for this is often the
sense of shame at having to admit that they trusted someone enough
to let them into their homes without checking identification first.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the plans, Clarke said "This is not a crime that the
Government can tackle alone. Organizations that send out people
for home visits have an enormous role to play and I am very
pleased that many organizations have agreed to support this
campaign." 
</P>
</TEXT>
