<HEADLINE> Wars in Angola, Congo Make Refugee Problem Worse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The civil conflicts in Angola and
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) are making the
humanitarian crisis deteriorating on the African continent, a
high-ranking United Nations refugee official said here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The (southern African) region has more refugees than five
years ago. The situation has become more volatile, it has in fact
deteriorated," said Nicholas Bwakira, director for the southern
African region of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
Zambia is now home to 400,000 refugees fleeing conflicts in
Angola and the DRC, while Namibia is sheltering 10,000 Angolan
refugees, said Bwakira.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. plans to add 60 million U.S. dollars in aid to 250
million U.S. dollars already pledged by international donors this
year to help refugees in Angola.
</P>
<P>
At this moment, Africa is home to 3.3 million refugees and 15
million internally displaced people, according to the official,
who said that the U. N. refugee agency spent up to 300 million
U.S. dollars a year on refugees in Africa, and that this figure
could rise unless Africa reined in conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
