<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade in "Living Fossil" Fish Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The 11th Conference of the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
decided here on Wednesday to accord protection to some of the
world's lesser-known species like coelacanth.
</P>
<P>
Coelacanth, a "living fossil" fish and once thought to have
become extinct with the dinosaurs, was put into Appendix I of the
convention, which bans any trade in the species.
</P>
<P>
The 150-nation conference also agreed to ban trade in
Australia's dugongs, a type of sea cow, and strengthen
conservation measures for Asian box turtles and African spurred
tortoises, which are caught wild and sold into the global pet
trade.
</P>
<P>
But proposals for a total ban on trade in species of musk deer
and Black Sea bottlenose dolphins were rejected.
</P>
<P>
The 11-day conference due to end on Thursday earlier this week
upheld long-standing bans on trade in ivory, whales and marine
turtles, but refused to protect great white sharks, whale sharks
and basking sharks.
</P>
<P>
The convention already provides varying levels of protection to
more than 30,000 plant and animal species and the number keeps
increasing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
