about the current turmoil in Zimbabwe, President Mbeki's
spokeswoman Tasneem Carrim said in Pretoria on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The issue must be resolved by getting all the affected parties
to sit down and talk. South Africa is prepared to help in
whatever way it can to facilitate such consultative process. That
is our position at the moment," she said.
</P>
<P>
Carrim reiterated Mbeki's stance is that the land issue in
Zimbabwe is a historical problem that has to be resolved, which
will possibly require the United Kingdom to honor an undertaking
to make funds available for land reform in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, asked at a joint news conference held by South
African Public Enterprises Minister Jeff Radebe and Mozambican
Finance and Planning Minister Luica Diogo whether the two
ministers had discussed Zimbabwe's turmoil during the meeting,
Radebe said: "Not at all. It was a meeting between South Africa
and Mozambique. Only bilateral issues were discussed."
</P>
<P>
"I can't express any view (on Zimbabwe) right now. The
statements that were made by our president speak for themselves,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
