<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Not to Intervene in Zimbabwe's Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) will not intervene in Zimbabwe's
internal affairs or publicly pressurize President Robert Mugabe,
Mozambican and South African presidential spokesmen said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to South African Press Association, a spokesman for
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano, who chairs the SADC, said
in a telephone interview: "At the moment it is our belief that
the Zimbabweans can resolve their own problems."
</P>
<P>
Things has not got out of hand in Zimbabwe and the SADC's
priorities are the civil wars in Angola and the Democratic
Republic of the Congo, the spokesman stressed.
</P>
<P>
There is no need for a special SADC mission to Zimbabwe as the
SADC heads of state are in routine telephone contact with Mugabe
and each other and Chissano's view is that the instability in
Zimbabwe can be stopped if the genuine desire of its people for
land can be resolved, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South African President Thabo Mbeki has so far
resisted pressure to publicly condemn the illegal occupation of
white-owned farms in Zimbabwe by Mugabe's supporters and war
veterans, the presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would neither confirm nor deny media reports
that Mbeki is leading a secret regional initiative to resolve the
crisis in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
A state visit by Mbeki to Zimbabwe is on the cards, but the
date has not been decided yet, Mankahlana said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
