<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Draft Peace Deal to Be Ready by June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The draft proposals for
Burundi peace deal may be ready by June, a member of the
facilitation team for Burundi peace talks hinted on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in northern Tanzanian town of
Arusha, the chairman of the Democracy and Good Governance
Committee for the peace talks Nicholas Hayssom said the
facilitation team will meet early next month in Arusha to prepare
the draft proposals, which will later be given to the 19 concerned
parties at the talks for response.
</P>
<P>
Since the negotiations are now more focused than ever, said
Hayssom, a professor from South Africa, "I'm optimistic that a
peace deal is possible." "Holding meetings and listening have made
us understand better the issues," the chairman noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the committee he heads has not achieved a
breakthrough on contentious issues like the electoral system and
the transitional instruments.
</P>
<P>
He has asked the delegates to present by the end of this month
their written suggestions that will be the basis for the
facilitation team to draw proposals.
</P>
<P>
Around 200,000 people, most of them civilians, have lost their
lives since the outbreak of war in the tiny central African
country in 1993 between Hutu rebels and the army, dominated by the
minority Tutsi ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks, which began in Arusha in June 1998, are
currently taking place in four committees, dealing respectively
with the nature of the Burundi conflict, democracy and good
governance, peace and security for all and economic reconstruction
and the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen Burundian parties, including two deposed presidents,
are attending the talks, currently under the mediation of former
South African president Nelson Mandela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
