<HEADLINE> Red Cross Convoys Bring Food to Ethiopian Drought Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Convoys of the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) have brought deliveries of food
this week to the drought-hit Denan, some 600 kilometers southeast
of the capital Addis Ababa of Ethiopia, a press release from ICRC
said.
</P>
<P>
The pre-cooked fortified food will be distributed to all of the
more than 14,500 people in Denan who are battling for survival
against drought that has devastated their livelihood, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the severity of the food crisis, the ICRC release
said, " An assessment carried out by an ICRC team nine days ago
confirmed that the situation is extremely critical with large
numbers of women, children and elderly seriously malnourished and
a very high death toll."
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the first phase of the relief
operation aims at stabilizing the critical situation and stemming
malnutrition by providing the whole population of four affected
districts in Gode zone with regular and carefully balanced
nutrients.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ICRC said it has begun stockpiling items such as
shelter and other emergency items which could be quickly needed if
the long-awaited rains begin to fall in the zone as well as
putting into plans for a seeds distribution program to 18,600
families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
