<HEADLINE> 29 Cases of Wild Polio Virus Infection in Bangladesh Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Around 500 children infected with
acute flaccid paralysis were detected in Bangladesh last year, of
whom 29 cases of deadly wild poliomyelitis virus (WPV) are
positive, experts of the Extended Program of Immunization (EPI)
revealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On the Eve of the 7th National Immunization Day (NID), the EPI
experts said of the WPV-positive, 12 cases were found in
Chittagong, the second largest city in the country.
</P>
<P>
They said that the number of children infected with deadly WPV
is reportedly increasing, and the Chittagong Division has so far
been considered as a vulnerable area in comparison to other
divisions.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the coverage of the polio vaccine rose to around
97 percent during the last six years. However, they admitted that
about one million children were left out from the polio vaccine
last year.
</P>
<P>
The government has undertaken an intensified NID program by
administering polio vaccines among the children of urban areas,
slums, enclaves refugee camps and hilly areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chittagong district administration has
undertaken a special measure to administer polio and tetanus
vaccines among the children and women of 13 remote areas with the
help of helicopters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
