<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Hits New High in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit hit a
new high of 29.2 billion U.S. dollars in February as Americans'
demand for foreign oil hit an all-time monthly high while sales of
exports dipped, the Commerce Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deficit increased by 6.5 percent in February compared to a
deficit of 27.4 billion dollars posted in January. February's
deficit was bigger than the 28.9-billion-dollar imbalance many
analysts were forecasting.
</P>
<P>
Total imports climbed 1.5 percent to a record 113.4 billion
dollars in February as sales of chemicals and other industrial
supplies and of capital goods including computers and
telecommunications equipment rose to records.
</P>
<P>
Imports of foreign petroleum climbed to 9.6 billion dollars in
February, pushing the oil trade deficit to a record 8.8 billion
dollars. The price of crude oil hit 25.01 dollars per barrel in
February, the highest since 25.75 dollars in December 1990 on the
eve of the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Total U.S. exports slipped by 0.2 percent to 84.2 billion
dollars in February, held back by civilian aircraft exports which
fell to 1.6 billion dollars from 2.6 billion dollars the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months of this year, the deficit was 56.7
billion dollars, compared with 34.8 billion dollars during the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
For all of last year, the deficit soared to an all-time high of
267.6 billion dollars, 62.9 percent above the previous record, an
imbalance of 164.3 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade deficit with Japan shot up 20.7 percent to 6.7
billion dollars in February. And, the deficit with countries
belonging to the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries hit
a monthly high of 3.2 billion dollars, a 21.4 percent increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lake Ontario Regains Water Level with Fast Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- One of the North American Great
Lakes,Lake Ontario, is fast regaining its water supply due to
above average rain and snow in the region for the past two weeks,
Canada's National Post newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"If average water supply conditions prevail over the next few
months, Lake Ontario could rise above seasonal average," the
newspaper quoted the Canadian Department of Environment as
predicting.
</P>
<P>
According to the most recent measurement data, the newspaper
said,Lake Ontario sits at an elevation of 74.8 meters, about eight
centimeters lower than the average for this time of the year, but
80 centimeters higher than the record low for April set in 1935.
</P>
<P>
While water supply is increasing for Lake Ontario, water levels
on Lakes Michigan, Huron, Superior and Erie are at their lowest
levels in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
Lakes Michigan and Huron are the lowest of all at 51
centimeters below the April average. Lake Erie sits 24 centimeters
below average while Lake Superior is 16 centimeters below the long-
term normal level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
