<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Protests EU's Decision to Tighten Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia on Wednesday lodged
its "strongest protest" against a decision made earlier by leaders
of the European Union (EU) to tighten its current financial
sanctions against the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Slamming the decision as "unilateral and illegal," the Yugoslav
Foreign Ministry said in a statement that it will pose a serious
threat to the life of the country's poor, and is completely in
violation of international law and the EU's established policies.
</P>
<P>
At an informal summit on March 24 in Lisbon, Portugal, the
leaders of the 15 EU nations agreed to keep up political and
economic pressure on Yugoslavia, including tightening financial
sanctions, despite their endorsement of a six-month suspension of
a commercial flight ban on the country.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia's Foreign Ministry said the move is designed to
support certain international forces in creating ongoing
disturbances in the Balkans and impeding the integration process
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia hopes the EU will come to know the harm of its
present policies, and will remove immediately all the sanctions
and other restrictions hindering the normal development of
bilateral relations on the basis of equality and mutual benefit,
it added.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia, made up of Serbia and Montenegro, has been under
strict sanctions imposed by the United States and the EU since
1992 because of its involvement in the Bosnian War.
</P>
<P>
After the war NATO launched in Kosovo last year, the U.S. and
the EU imposed a ban on air links with the country and stepped up
financial restrictions. The air embargo was lifted late last month
for a period of six months with the possibility of lifting it
permanently in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
