<HEADLINE> Italian Prime Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema has resigned following heavy losses of his center-left
coalition in Sunday's regional elections.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema's resignation was accepted Wednesday evening by
President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Now Italy will either form a new centre-left government or face
early general elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, D'Alema admitted in the Senate that Sunday's
defeat was a blow both for himself and his government. It was
clear that his government has lost a vote of confidence, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, D'Alema said, Sunday's vote was in no way one against
the current legislature and therefore the legislature should
continue to work to push forward a referendum scheduled for May 21
which is aimed at reforming the electoral law.
</P>
<P>
There are only eleven months left for the mandate of the
current legislature, D'Alema said. Time should be used to
consolidate economic and social reforms and to draft a new
electoral law.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema promised that he will remain at the service of the
center-left government in whatever capacity and that he will be
personally involved in the campaign for next month's referendum.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema tendered his resignation to Ciampi on Monday but the
resignation was rejected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
