GENEVA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) recommended independent drug observers to the
Sydney Olympics, insuring the drug tests to be open to the
athletes and the public during the September 15-October 1 Games,
the IOC said in Lausanne, Switzerland, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Rogge, vice chairman of the IOC's medical commision,
said the new World Anti-Doping Agency will appoint the independent
observers to watch over the entire drug testing system at all
stages, including the collection and analysis of urine samples and
disciplinary hearings for athletes who test positive.
</P>
<P>
Critics from athletes' groups and the public have accused the
IOC of under-the-table hadling of positive tests at past Olympics.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 2,000 drugs test expected to be carried out
during the Sydney Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
