<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Calls for Talks with UAE over Island Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Wednesday called for cordial talks and understanding with the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) to solve their territorial dispute over
three Gulf islands.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way for removal of the ongoing misunderstandings
between Iran and the UAE except cordial talks and understanding,"
Khatami told reporters together with his Yemeni counterpart
Abdullah Saleh, who is ending a three-day visit to Iran and leaving
for the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Khatami hoped the UAE would respond to this Iranian "
humanitarian request" for talks, understanding and agreement, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We have had no enmity with the UAE and have always extended
hands of friendship towards our UAE brothers and I hope we will one
day witness how misunderstandings can be removed on the basis of
understanding," Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the three southern Gulf islands of Abu Mussa, the
Greater and Lesser Tunbs after the British forces withdrew from the
region in 1971. Both Tehran and Abu Dhabi claimed full sovereignty
over the islands.
</P>
<P>
The UAE repeatedly called for international arbitration to solve
the dispute, but Iran insisted that the issue should be settled by
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni president said he discussed the Iran-UAE territorial
dispute with Iranian officials and hoped the question would be
solved amicably.
</P>
<P>
He had contacted UAE President Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al-
Nahayan before he arrived in Tehran on Monday for a three-day
official visit, during which he held talks with Iranian supreme
leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, President Khatami and Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi.
</P>
<P>
Khatami reiterated that Iran's principled policy is based on
detente and consolidation and expansion of relations with regional
states.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that if good intention, mutual respect and logic
exist, no problem will remain unsolved," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that through cooperation and reliance on mutual
interests, "we should move towards consolidating security and
stability in the region and realization of this will benefit all
regional states."
</P>
<P>
He cited Iran's recent release of Iraqi prisoners of war, saying
that based on the policy of detente, the two neighbors are moving
toward solving problems and maintaining stability in relations.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought an eight year war in the 1980s, which
Khatami said served the "interests of foreigners," and cost about 1
million lives from both sides.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said Iran is ready to move towards a security pact with
regional neighbors, as part of security arrangements in the area.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally such an accord would be based on non-intervention in
each other's internal affairs, mutual respect and honoring
interests of all regional states," he said.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that security in the region should be provided by
regional states, and hope that in the near future, the regional
states would witness establishment of security through cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Lebanese Detainees Released After Court Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The 13 Lebanese prisoners, who
had been held in Israeli custody for over a decade, were set free
by Israel Wednesday afternoon as a ruling of Israel's Supreme Court
finally cleared the way for the release.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners were turned over by Israel to the International
Red Cross Organization, which will in turn return them to their
families, at a crossing point in Israeli-Lebanese border, Israel
Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross bus carrying them is now heading to the Lebanon
side of the border, where their relatives are waiting for them,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
These Lebanese citizens, who had been held in administrative
detention without a trial as bargaining chips for the return or
information of missing Israeli servicemen in Lebanon, are handed
over by Israeli prison officials to Israeli army at about 5 a.m.
(0200 GMT) Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
They were at a border military base to wait for the Supreme
Court ruling on the last-minute petition against their freedom by
the family of missing Israel Air Force navigator Ron Arad.
</P>
<P>
Before the court, Arad's mother issued an emotional plea to the
judges, urging them to look at a soldier's mother in the eyes and
not to abandon her son, who might still be alive, somewhere in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, the justices' panel had not let their sympathy win
over professional legal weighing in the case. They rejected the
appeal, saying it is anyway illegal to keep these Lebanese citizens
as they are not posing threats to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
The court deliver the landmark ruling last Wednesday to order
immediate release of eight Lebanese hostages, which prompted the
prison authority to act to set another five free as the principle
of ruling also applied to those ones.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak promised Tuesday to begin an immediate
legislative process to examine and permit the holding of future
bargaining chips in accordance with the concept in international
law.
</P>
<P>
The proposed legislation reportedly would shift the decision on
detention from the courts to the defense minister and keep "illegal
fighters", or guerrillas, by methods other than administrative
detention.
</P>
<P>
However, due to pressure by Justice Minister Yossi Beilin, the
plan to pass the law through a fast track schedule was shelved and
the legislation draft is due to be debated in earlier May, which
will be too late for holding these 13 Lebanese prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two most prominent detainees Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid
and Mustafa Dirani, are expected to be held in Israeli prison for
at least one more month, as the Tel Aviv District Court had set May
8 as the date for next hearing of the government's appeal to extend
their detention.
</P>
<P>
Barak's government had made a special effort to guarantee the
continued detainment in Israel of Dirani and Obeid.
</P>
<P>
Israelis regard the two, who belonged to Lebanese anti-
occupation Hezbollah and Amal militias respectively, as figures
posing great danger to the Jewish state's security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
