<HEADLINE> 13 Freed Lebanese Detainees Arrive in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The 13 Lebanese detainees who were
freed by Israel and delivered to the International Red Cross
Organization have arrived in Lebanon Wednesday afternoon, People's
Sound radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Lebanese, imprisoned by Israel for more than a decade
without trial, were held by Israel as bargaining chips for
exchanging the missing Israeli air force navigator Ron Arad,
allegedly held by Lebanese anti-Israel resistance movements.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,500 people of the detainees' relatives and reporters had
gathered at the border station of Kafer Tibeneen since Wednesday
morning for their return.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Israeli High Court ruled that it is illegal for
Israel to hold prisoners in the hope of swapping them for missing
soldiers. However, the release was postponed twice.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the court rejected a petition, submitted by Arad's
family, asking for a panel of 13 judges to review the ruling to
release the detainees. The family submitted a petition again late
Tuesday in an effort to bypass the landmark High Court's release
ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
