<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: 131 Killed in Philippines' Worst Air Mishap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- All 131 people on board the Air
Philippines Flight 541 were killed when the jet crash-landed
Wednesday morning in Samal Island near Davao City in the southern
Philippines, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Philippine National Disaster Coordinating
Council (NDCC), the Boeing 737-200 with 124 passengers and seven
crew members on board crashed at around 07:20 local time (23:20
GMT, Tuesday) in Mount Caanlangan of Samal Island, some 1,000
kilometers south of Manila.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated Davao-bound aircraft left Manila at around 05:20
local time (21:20 GMT, Tuesday) and was reported missing at about
07:05 local time (23:05 GMT, Tuesday), said the NDCC.
</P>
<P>
Air and land rescue recovery teams that arrived more than an
hour after the disaster in the rugged highland of the island said
the aircraft was in total wreck while the passengers and crew were
badly mangled.
</P>
<P>
Villagers said they heard two loud explosions as soon as the
aircraft zoomed down across coconut grove in the island some eight
kilometers east of the Davao International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Air Transportation Office Executive Director Rolando Luna
reported that Flight 541 circled Davao International Airport
before crashing into the coconut grove.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, airline officials said the Boeing 737-200 plane was
given its normal maintenance check before taking off and no
abnormalities were found.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Atmospheric Geophysical Astronomical Services
Administration said weather conditions at the time of the crash
were good and that there was no problem with visibility.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Etrada expressed sorrow over the
early morning crash and ordered concerned agencies to provide
assistance to relatives of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Secretaries Vicente Rivera of the Department of Transportation
and Communications and Orlando Mercado of the Department of
National Defense went to the crash site to investigate the
accident and oversee search and rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
Rivera said his department will investigate the events that led
to the fatal Air Philippines plane crash before deciding on
whether or not to ground the airline's other planes.
</P>
<P>
The investigators are trying to identify whether the tragedy was
caused by pilot error, mechanical problem, bad weather or a
combination of the three factors.
</P>
<P>
Another theory is the possibility of sabotage, in the wake of
reported threats of terrorists to wage war against the government
by bombing public facilities unless their demands are met.
</P>
<P>
Rivera said one of two flight boxes, which can shed light on
what actually transpired before the crash, has been recovered.
</P>
<P>
The Air Philippines Flight 541 tragedy is the worst air tragedy
in the country in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In February 1998, the Cebu Pacific Flight 387 exploded upon
impact in a mountainous area in the southern Cagayan de Oro City,
killing 104 persons.
</P>
<P>
In December 1999, an Asian Spirit aircraft with 17 persons on
board perished when it crash-landed in Nueva Ecija province in the
northern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
With intermittent rains, the slow and painstaking process of
picking pieces of bodies scattered at the impact area is still
going on despite the darkness.
</P>
<P>
Military and privately-owned helicopters took turns in ferrying
the wrapped cadavers from the retrieval site to the command center
at the Davao International Airport.
</P>
<P>
A welfare center to serve the kins of the crash victims of the
ill-fated plane has been established in Davao City.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Air Philippines spokesperson Lea Sison said the
airline will extend assistance to the relatives of those who
perished in the crash.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Vice-President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo, concurrently
Social Welfare Secretary, will be arriving at Davao City on
Thursday to personally assure that all needed assistance can be
extended to the families of the victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
