<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Launch Fresh Offensive in North S.Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 19 (Xinhua) - Sri Lanka's Tamil Tiger rebels
have launched a fresh offensive against military positions along a
strategic highway in northern Jaffna to mark the fifth anniversary
of what is known as Eelam War III which fell on Wednesday,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued from their office in London late on
Tuesday, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels said
that fierce fighting had erupted in the Thenmarachchi sector of
the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"Having wiped out several kilometers of the front defense lines
of the Sri Lankan troops in Maser and Soranpattu areas the LTTE
forces are advancing deep into the area," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Many bloody battles have been reported in the past four weeks
since the rebels tried to dislodge government troops from key
positions near the A-9 highway in Jaffna. Hundreds of rebels and
soldiers have been killed or wounded in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
The present bout of fighting broke out on April 19, 1995 when
the LTTE pulled out of a truce that lasted just 100 days, and is
known as Eelam War III, or the third stage of the LTTE's campaign
for a homeland for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Defense said Wednesday that 12 government
soldiers were killed and 43 wounded when repulsing the rebel
onslaught on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that the rebels also suffered
heavy casualties.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE statement said fighting had started Tuesday afternoon
when the guerrillas launched an "offensive thrust" and was
continuing late into the night.
</P>
<P>
It didn't give details of casualties but said Tamil rebel
combatants have recovered large quantities of weapons and
ammunition left behind by government troops.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman confirmed that heavy clashes continued in
the region Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have engaged each other with artillery and
mortars in a bid to keep control of the strategic A-9 highway that
connects Jaffna with the strategic military complex of Elephant
Pass, a narrow causeway linking the peninsula with the rest of
country.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had vowed to wrest control of Jaffna, some 400
kilometers north of the capital Colombo, which was their
stronghold until the army took it back in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
