<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, UK Vow to Boost Asia-Europe Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook and his Thai counterpart Surin Pitsuwan
Wednesday appealed for further strengthening the cooperation
between Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held here Wednesday, the two
foreign ministers stressed that as the first and the second host
of the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM), Thailand and Britain are "
determined to boost the cooperation between the two continents."
</P>
<P>
They said the relationship between the European Union (EU) and
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) are also to be
further enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that last week the European Commission approved the
plan to restart the EU-ASEAN ministerial talks, which will be
resumed later this year.
</P>
<P>
Surin noted that the two countries are now prepared to attend
the third Asia-Europe Meeting, which is to be held on October 20--
21 this year in Seoul, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that he had held "constructive talks" with Thai
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai and Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan Wednesday Morning, discussing bilateral, regional,
welfare, trade and other issues.
</P>
<P>
Cook arrived here last night, as the second stop of his three-
nation Asian tour. He started his trip on April 15, with India as
the first leg, followed by Thailand and Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Cook will leave here and fly to Nepal on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
