<HEADLINE> Top Legislature to Inspect Enforcement of Law on Land Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Standing Committee of National
People's Congress (NPC) will send three inspection teams to
Guangdong, Hubei and Jiangsu Provinces next month to inspect the
enforcement of Laws on Land Management.
</P>
<P>
At the 1st meeting of the inspection teams held today in
Beijing, Zou Jiahua, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee,
said that the enforcement of the Law on Land Management has
yielded excellent results. Arable land for construction purposes
in 1999 was 205,100 hectares, 76,000 hectares less than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
China's land resource are severely limited. Arable land totals
130 million hectares with 0.1 hectares per capita. The protection
of arable land is vital, Zou stressed.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, ministers from land and resources,
construction, communications, agriculture and forestry
administration ministries delivered reports on the enforcement of
the law and decided to find effective ways to tackle problems
arising from the enforcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
