<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canal Project Proposed to Dig Thailand Out of Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Kra Canal project will help
pull Thailand out of present economic crisis and act as an
impetus to the country's economy, a long time advocate of the
project said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Pakdee Tananpura, an adviser to
the Subcommittee for the Study of the Kra Canal Project under the
House Committee on Military Affairs, said the economic crisis has
jeopardized the national security of Thailand, leaving thousands
of businesses failed and 4 million people unemployed.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, the canal project, which represents an
investment of approximately 20 billion U.S. dollars, can jump-
start the country's economy by providing 3 million jobs and
numerous business chances, Pakdee said.
</P>
<P>
The Kra Canal, named for the narrowest part of the peninsula
Thailand shares with Malaysia, will link the Gulf of Thailand of
the Pacific Ocean and the Andaman Sea of the Indian Ocean, and
provide some 1,660-kilometer shortcut for European freighters and
Middle East oil tankers traveling to and from East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Pakdee admitted that by using the Kra Canal rather than going
through the Malacca Strait ships would save only 36 hours instead
of days and weeks as is the case for the Panama Canal and the Suez
Canal.
</P>
<P>
However, he argued, the feasibility of the Kra Canal lies in
the fact that it will help ease the traffic congestion in the
Malacca Strait.
</P>
<P>
He said approximately 40 percent of world liner shipment of
containerized cargo in the year 1997 was traded in the Asia-
Pacific region, and there are approximately 150,000 ships passing
through the Malacca Strait with an expected annual growth of 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2020, there will most likely be over 450,000 ships
going through the strait, Pakdee said.
</P>
<P>
"If the Kra Canal is constructed by the year 2020, it will
definitely help ease the traffic congestion in the Malacca Strait,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Construction contractors from Japan, Germany, France and China
have expressed investment interest in the project, Pakdee said.
</P>
<P>
However, the committee needs to lobby hard to persuade the Thai
public and government to buy the idea, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
