<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science Proves Prince Died in Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Belgian and German scientists have
proved through genetic analysis that the son of France's King
Louis XVI and Queen Marie-Antoinette died in a Paris prison in
1795.
</P>
<P>
Through analysis of the DNA taken from his heart, a 10-year-
old boy who died of tuberculosis in a tower of the Temple prison
in Paris in June 1795 was determined to be Louis XVII, Agence
France Presse reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Jean-Jacques Cassiman of the University of Louvain in
Belgium and Professor Ernst Brinckmann of the University of
Munster in Germany proved genes taken from the heart of the boy
were identical to those of his mother and aunts and two
descendants of the former French royal family.
</P>
<P>
After the boy died on June 8, 1795, a doctor named Philippe-
Jean Pelletan made an autopsy of his body and took his heart,
which he kept in a box filled with wine to prevent it from
decaying.
</P>
<P>
The heart has been kept since 1975 in the Basilique of Saint-
Denis north of Paris, where the remains of Louis XVI and Queen
Marie-Antoinette were also kept.
</P>
<P>
The king and the queen were executed by guillotine in January
1793 during the rein of terror by Jacobin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0098 </DOCNO>
