<HEADLINE> Former Russian PM Appointed Audit Chamber Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Russia's lower house of parliament
on Wednesday appointed former prime minister Sergei Stepashin as
head of the country's Audit Chamber.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was approved by a vote of 309-29 with 10
abstentions in the State Duma, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Audit Chamber is a government fiscal control body formed
by the Federal Assembly (parliament) and accountable to it. The
chamber exercises control over the timely execution of the federal
budget and federal non-budget funds.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, who had also served as interior minister before the
start of his three-month premiership last May, laid out his plan
to improve the effectiveness of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
The body should become the chief financial tool to supervise
the use of budget funds and fight corruption, he said.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, who also heads the Corruption Fighting Committee,
said the Audit Chamber should continuously cooperate with the
president, both houses of parliament and the cabinet, which it has
failed to do so far.
</P>
<P>
He called for amending the legislation to make the chamber
more accountable and powerful. He also pledged to avoid
unnecessary politicking in the operations of the Audit Chamber,
noting that various lobbies had in the past tried to use the
chamber to serve their own purposes.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin was elected to the State Duma last December as a
leader of the liberal Yabloko movement from St. Petersburg.
</P>
</TEXT>
