<HEADLINE> Belgian Medical Agency Says No to British Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian Royal Academy of
Medicine is advising against the import of blood and blood
products from Britain, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The medical agency said anyone who spent longer than six months
in Britain between 1980 and 1996 should also not donate blood.
</P>
<P>
The measures are meant to protect Belgians against the possible
transfer of Creutzfeldt Jacob disease -- the human variant of Mad
Cow disease.
</P>
<P>
Professor Jean Plum of the Royal Academy of Medicine said that
the highest prevalence of the disease has been in Britain, and
Creutzfeldt Jacob could be transferred through blood.
</P>
<P>
It is therefore better to take precautionary measures omitting
British blood products from supplies in Belgium, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
