<HEADLINE> Qatari Emir Hopes to Boost Ties With Bahrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin
Khalifa al-Thani voiced hope on Wednesday that the arrival of
Bahrain's first ambassador would help enhance relations between the
two small Gulf Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Hamad made the remarks in the Qatari capital Doha when receiving
credentials presented by Bahraini Ambassador to Qatar Essa Mohammed
Al-Jame, according to a report by the Kuwait News Agency from Doha.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari monarch hoped Al-Jame would be successful in carrying
out his mission in strengthening the recently improved ties between
Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Qatar and Bahrain agreed to exchange ambassadors during a
landmark visit to Bahrain by the Qatari emir, which took place on
December 28, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In their summit meeting, Hamad and his Bahraini counterpart
Sheikh Hamad Bin Isa al-Khalifa also agreed to set up a joint
committee to try to settle a border dispute through cordial means.
</P>
<P>
Doha and Manama are locked in a dispute over several small but
potentially oil-and-gas-rich Gulf isles, including the Hawar
islands, which are controlled by Bahrain since 1930s but also
claimed by Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The issue has been taken to the International Court of Justice,
waiting for a verdict.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries have agreed that the case will be
withdrawn if an acceptable solution is reached before the court's
verdict by the joint committee, which is co-chaired by their crown
princes.
</P>
<P>
On January 6, the Bahraini emir visited Doha, just nine days
after Qatari emir's trip to Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
During the exchange of visits, both sides reiterated that the
long-running border standoff should not hamper bilateral
cooperation in all other fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
