<HEADLINE> Philippine Terrorist Group Beheads 2 Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine extremist group Abu
Sayyaf beheaded Wednesday two of their 29 hostages after the
government rejected their demand to ask the United States to
release three Arab terrorists jailed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sabaya, spokesman of the Muslim fundamentalist group,
announced the execution of the two hostages during a live radio
interview Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
However, the Armed Forces of the Philippines declined to
confirm the reported beheading incident, saying they would wait
for verification by their men in Basilan province where the
hostages have been held since March this year.
</P>
<P>
The two hostages were executed at 3:15 Wednesday afternoon,
Sabaya said, adding that the group will behead more hostages every
time the Presidential Palace "makes a negative statement."
</P>
<P>
Sabaya did not identify the executed hostages, except that they
were reportedly former soldiers turned teachers. Sabaya said there
are still 27 hostages in their hands.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf had give a 3 p.m. deadline Wednesday for the
government to relay their demands to the U.S. government for the
release of three Arab international terrorists imprisoned in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Another Abu Sayyaf demand is for the government to send an
additional 85 sacks of rice. They had earlier asked for 200 sacks
of rice which the Crisis Management Committee (CMC) reluctantly
granted.
</P>
<P>
The CMC is handling the negotiations with the Abu Sayyaf for
the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim extremist group has also threatened to kill or
kidnap Americans in the country after the Philippine government
rejected their demands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Basilan Governor Wahab Akbar warned the Abu Sayyaf
that he will personally lead the assault of the terrorists'
mountain lair in the province if the fundamentalist group would
not release the hostages by April 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
