<HEADLINE> Nigerian Presidency, Legislature Seek Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo and principal officials of the country's top legislature,
the National Assembly, have opened talks on their recent raw over
budget, presidential jet and other issues.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, Wednesday cited
sources as saying that both sides had pledged to sheath their
swords.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which came a day after Obasanjo returned from the
G-77 summit Monday, was attended by Senate President William
Okadigbo and Deputy Speaker of the House of Representatives
Chibudom Nwuche, among others, on the legislative side.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Obasanjo as telling the Assemblymen that he
and the Nigerian delegation to the G-77 summit were "distracted
and embarrassed by the spate of media war between the Presidency
and the legislature within the past one week."
</P>
<P>
He said it was unbecoming for such high officials in a country
to engage in open bickering like "school kids".
</P>
<P>
The development was much worse as such hot exchange of words
could raise tempers within the polity and send wrong signals to
both Nigerians and the international community that there was a
crisis within the Nigerian leadership, he added.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the law makers, Senate leader Okadigbo said the
Assembly leadership did not join in the open feud as their aides
simply replied those of the Presidency to set the record straight
in the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
He complained about the scathing press reports, accusing them
of portraying the Assembly in poor light.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo called for a truce while both sides and the ruling
People's Democratic Party (PDP) work out the differences,
especially on the year 2000 budget and other matters.
</P>
<P>
Both parties agreed to meet regularly, especially whenever
disagreements arise between them.
</P>
<P>
However, no details on the discussion pertaining to Senator
Arthur Nzeribe, who had initiated an impeachment move against
Obasanjo, was released.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between the Presidency and the legislature of
Nigeria had been particularly frosty for about two weeks, with
operatives of both sides engaging in a media war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
