<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Confirms Resignation Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema announced Wednesday that he would resign to take
responsibility for the center-left party's defeat in last Sunday's
regional elections.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema told the Senate that he would meet President Carlo
Azeglio Ciampi later Wednesday to confirm his decision to resign.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema admitted that Sunday's defeat was a blow both for
himself and his government.
</P>
<P>
Although there was no institutional obligation for the
government to resign, D'Alema said, it was clear that his
government has lost a vote of confidence and it was best that it
resign.
</P>
<P>
However, D'Alema stressed, Sunday's vote was in no way one
against the current legislature and therefore there was no reason
for it to be dissolved.
</P>
<P>
There are only eleven months left for the mandate of the
current legislature, D'Alema said. Time should be used to
consolidate economic and social reforms and to draft a new
electoral law, he said.
</P>
<P>
Looking back at the performance of his 18-month executive, the
premier recalled the achievements made in both the economic and
social areas but admitted that more could have been done.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema promised that he will remain at the service of the
center-left government in whatever capacity and that he will be
personally involved in the campaign for next week's referendum on
electoral law reform. 
</P>
