<HEADLINE> Violin Maestro Postpones Beijing Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- World violin maestro Kyung-Wha
Chung delayed her Beijing debut because of illness, performance
organizers announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Chung caught a bad cold recently and will not complete her
performance tour to Europe, which was formerly scheduled in late
April, and also the Beijing concert, Gong Xiaozhuang, senior
project manager of the Century Performance Corporation, told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
But Chung won't disappoint her Chinese audience: her agent has
re-scheduled her performance to May 10 at the Century Theater.
</P>
<P>
The corporation also announced that tickets for the April 24
concert can be used for the May performance.
</P>
<P>
In a career that has spanned more than 25 years, Chung has
gained international fame and performed with many prominent
orchestras.
</P>
<P>
Chung is expected to play Suite No. 3 in D Major by J. B. Bach,
Sonata for Violin and Piano by Claude Debussy, Violin Sonata in A
Major by C. Franck, Violin Sonata by Ludwig van Beethoven, and
Tzigane by Maurice Ravel.  
