<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB:hke041953 -- Roundup: Nepal Strives to Promote Trade, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Realizing that promoting foreign trade and investment is a
vital way out for the poverty-ridden and landlocked Himalayan
kingdom, the government led by Prime Minister G.P. Koirala has
made economic diplomacy a top agenda in its foreign policy,
focusing on issues of expanding foreign trade, taking in
investments and promoting Nepal as an attractive tourist
destination.
</P>
<P>
As Nepal is one of the poorest countries in the world, with an
annual per capita income of merely 200 U.S. dollars and about 45
percent of its 22 million population living below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Since Koirala came into power for the third time last month, he
has stressed on various occasions the importance of economic
diplomacy and pledged to create friendly environment to promote
trade and investments.
</P>
<P>
While inaugurating the Export Promotion Meeting--2000 on April
5,Koirala encouraged foreign investors and businessmen to put more
investment in his country, pledging to extend full support and
cooperations.
</P>
<P>
"You can invest in whatever sector you desire," Koirala said. "
In addition to selected manufacturing and service industries,
tourism and water resources are the prominent areas of foreign
investment in Nepal, " the prime minister elaborated.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that Nepal has become a better place for investment
and trade in the South Asian region, Koirala said the trade policy
in the country has been further liberalized by eliminating
quantitative restriction and import licenses and by reducing and
rationalizing tariff rates.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Export Promotion Meeting, organized by the
Ministry of Industry and Commerce, was the climax of a series of
trade promotion meetings and trade fairs in the recent month,
including"Tradex-2000" on March 30-April 3, "Trade Fair-2000" on
April 4-8, and so on.
</P>
<P>
The one-month long trade and investment promotion activities
were the initiative steps taken by the government in achieving its
targets.
</P>
<P>
The largest and most significant of all was the Export
Promotion Meeting-2000, the first-ever international trade meeting
in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the meeting were about 450 delegates,
representing 34 countries including Australia, Canada, China,
Japan, India,Britain, France, Germany, Russia and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The meeting and fair provided foreign diplomats and businessmen
with a unique opportunity to hear detailed policy preference from
the concerned ministers and business leaders on Nepal's continued
efforts towards promoting foreign trade, seeking foreign markets,
attracting foreign investment and projecting the country's image
as tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
Foreign employment, export and tourism are three biggest
earners of foreign currency for Nepal. According to statistics,
tourism income in 1998 reached 152.5 million U.S. dollars,
representing 4 percent of the country's GNP, while foreign workers
remitted 990 million U.S. dollars in 1997, accounting for nearly
25 percent of its GNP.
</P>
<P>
However, Nepal has long suffered from trade deficit, though the
export was the biggest foreign currency earner excluding labor
export.
</P>
<P>
Statistics by the Finance Ministry showed that in 1997/1998
fiscal year, export stood at 392.4 million U.S. dollars while
import reached 1268.5 million U.S. dollars, with a deficit of 876.
1 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
To further expand export and improve the trade deficit, the
government will soon formulate the National Export Policy to help
sustain export markets while guiding and protecting exporters,
according to an official of the National Planning Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
