<HEADLINE> Cholera Claims 70 Lives in Southern Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 70 people have died
of cholera in the drought-hit southern Somali region of Bay in the
past two days.
</P>
<P>
According to Madey Mukhtar Ali, chairman of Ufurow Commune,
some 20 km northwest of Qansahdhereh District, the worst affected
is Bulo Addey Village where the death has exceeded 40 people since
Tuesday after the people of the village began falling for the
disease in their dozens. He said the situation has steadily been
worsening since the beginning of the week.
</P>
<P>
The disease is now further spreading to more villages such as
Mushkah and Adad Wanleh where six and two deaths have been
reported respectively Wednesday morning and more villages south of
Qansahdhere District are now being affected.
</P>
<P>
According to the local authorities in Bay region the spread of
the disease is being supported by the drought which is forcing the
people to keep moving around in search of water and food.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of families are known to have fled their villages and
 countryside owing to the drought as no sufficient rains have
fallen in the region in the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
The governor of Bay region, Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinleh, said his
region is in desperate need of help owing to the combination of
droughts and cholera epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The worst affected districts are Dinsor and Qansahdhereh of Bay
region where more than 57 people died of cholera last week, which
makes the total death toll to nearly 130 people since the
beginning of the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
