<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Events for Rolling Back Malaria Summit Kicked off in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Some 250 Nigerian school children
Tuesday gathered under a symbolic mosquito net in Nigeria's
capital Abuja as part of a new campaign to popularize the use of
treated nets to curb the growing scourge of malaria.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration, marking the beginning of events for the
African summit to roll back malaria, was intended to demonstrate
the "possibility that malaria could be prevented, using cost
effective and simple methods such as insecticide treated bed
nets," the News Agency of Nigeria quoted officials of the World
Health Organization (WHO) as saying in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The organization said that the net, which is 225 times larger
than the conventional mosquito net would "served as a reminder
that 225 african children die of malaria every two and half hours
while over 2,173 children under the age of five die of malaria
every day."
</P>
<P>
The net which would enter the Guinness of records as the
largest of its type, would remain at the Eagle square, venue of
the country's May 29 hand- over, until the summit, expected to be
opened by President Olusegun Obasanjo on April 24.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's ceremony, Nigeria's first lady, Stella Obasanjo
said the demonstration "represents the beginning of a vigorous
and determined campaign to roll back malaria from our individual
countries."
</P>
<P>
Africa accounts for 90 percent of the worldwide Malaria
occurrence and Mrs Obasanjo said such measures would help end the
"payment of malaria tax" by millions of lives on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the net with immunization, she said "the efficacy and
benefits of insecticide treated bed nets have been well
established" and that the challenge was for those in endemic areas
to use it routinely.
</P>
<P>
The price of the nets, imported from abroad, varies between 450
naira (4. 5 U.S. dollars) for the cheapest to 7,500 naira (75
dollars) for the highest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preparatory Meeting for Inter-Korean Summit to Open at Panmunjom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A preparatory meeting for the inter-
Korean summit will be held Saturday at the truce village of
Panmunjom at 10 a.m. local time (0100GMT).
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang Wednesday informed Seoul of accepting its proposal on
the preparatory meeting for the summit which is scheduled for
Pyongyang on June 12-14.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
DPRK Red Cross President Jang Jae-on announced the acceptance to
his South Korean counterpart Chut Chung Won-shik by phone.
</P>
<P>
DPRK proposed to exchange letters to guarantee negotiation
delegations' safety at 9:30 a.m. Saturday through Red Cross
officials at Panmunjom, hoping that Seoul will accept the proposal.
</P>
<P>
If things go smoothly, inter-Korean government-level talks will
resume at the truce village six years after the preparatory
contact in June 1994.
</P>
<P>
South Korea Tuesday proposed that both Seoul and Pyongyang send
their five-member delegations led by vice minister-level officials
to attend the preparatory meeting.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, South Korea and DPRK reached an agreement in
China, under which South Korean President Kim Dae-jung will travel
to Pyongyang for a summit with DPRK leader Kim Jung-il.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first-ever inter-Korean summit since the Korean
War in the early 1950s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
