<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Pay More for Hospital Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Statistics of the Ministry of
Health (MOH) show that the Chinese are paying more for hospital
service, mainly because of higher medicine prices.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese now pays an average 79 yuan (about 9.5 US dollars)
per hospital outpatient visit and 2,891 yuan (about 348 US dollars)
for each hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
The costs are respectively 10 yuan and 300 yuan higher than the
figures one year ago, and the price hike has led to a successive
increase in medical expenditure in China.
</P>
<P>
Drug costs were found to make up 60 percent of the total
outpatient fee and 47 percent of the hospital admission fee,
becoming the leading cause of the expenditure increase.
</P>
<P>
In fact, rapid growth of drug prices in recent years has
brought steady complaints from those who can't afford the
treatment, as well as an outcry for medi-care reform to curb the
rise of medical costs.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is fashioning a medical insurance system
to cover hundreds of millions of urban workers, mainly aiming to
slow down the cost growth.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals will be forced to gradually eliminate highly
profitable drug sectors and turn them into tax-paying drugstores
to prevent doctors from prescribing expensive medicine to get
sales commissions.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that medical expenses differed at
different hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Several hospitals affiliated with MOH, ranked among China's
best hospitals, charge all patients 163 yuan in outpatient fees
and 7,961 yuan for the hospitalization fee, compared with 49 yuan
and 1,508 yuan at an ordinary county-level hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
