<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Fires Katyusha Rockets at Israeli Positions Along Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Hezbollah guerrillas Wednesday
morning fired 11 Katyusha rockets at Israeli positions in south
Lebanon near the international borders of Israel and Lebanon,
People's Sound radio reported.
</P>
<P>
According to security sources, the attacks were focused on the
position of Tayel Harfaa in the western sector of south Lebanon and
Hezbollah has claimed responsibility for the raids.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear whether the attacks caused any casualties.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak vowed Wednesday that his
country will retaliate if Hezbollah guerrillas continue firing
Katyushas to northern Israel or cause any casualties after its
troop withdrawal from south Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, the Israeli cabinet decided to endorse
Barak's pledge to bring the Israeli soldiers back home from south
Lebanon by July, with or without a peace agreement with Lebanon and
its main power broker Syria.
</P>
<P>
On Monday Israel formally notified the United Nations that it
will go ahead with the planned withdrawal by July.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied parts of south Lebanon since 1978. It set up
a self-styled security zone there in 1985 with a claimed aim of
protecting its northern borders from cross-border guerrilla
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, backed by Iran and Syria, has since
been engaged in a war of attrition to try to oust Israeli troops
and their ally South Lebanon Army from south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Repeats Rejection to U.N. Resolution 1284 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan has stressed that Iraq will never implement the U.N.
Security Council Resolution 1284 because it failed to respond to
Iraq's demand for a total lifting of the decade-old sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution, as a product of the British colonialist
mentality designed to put Iraq under its mandate, transferred Iraq
from conditional sanctions to everlasting embargo, Ramadan was
quoted as saying by the Iraqi News Agency (INA) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq does not pin hope on the U.N. Security Council to lift the
sanctions, but will let the embargo get eroded by itself, said
Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan is among the senior Iraqi officials who have recently
rejected the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz rejected
the U.N. Security Council decision to approve a new arms inspection
plan for Iraq, and reiterated Iraq's refusal to the Resolution
1284.
</P>
<P>
"I have never hinted that Iraq will cooperate with this
resolution," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, which created the U.N. Monitoring, Verification
and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) for Iraq, aims at resuming U.N.
arms inspections on Iraq, suspended since December 1998 when the U.
S. and Britain launched the Operation Desert Fox air strikes
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has since barred the U.N. arms inspectors from going back
and insisted that a total lifting of sanctions is the precondition
for their return.
</P>
<P>
The resolution offers to suspend sanctions for renewable 120-day
periods if U.N. arms inspectors report that Iraq has cooperated "in
all respects" with them and shown progress towards answering their
outstanding questions about its disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under crippling U.N. sanctions since its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. The sanctions cannot be lifted until the U.N.
Security Council certifies that Iraq is free of weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
