<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Calls for Immediate Action to Save Millions in Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 19 (Xinhua) --The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) has said that immediate action is crucial to save
the lives of millions of children and women in the Horn of Africa,
noting that no time can be lost to red tape or political inaction.
</P>
<P>
A UNICEF press release available here on Wednesday said that
UNICEF's offices in Ethiopia, Eritrea, Djibouti, Kenya and
Somalia, which are most directly threatened by the drought, are
focusing their relief efforts in the areas of health, nutrition,
water and sanitation.
</P>
<P>
Rodney Phillips, UNICEF's senior program officer in Ethiopia
said that " food is essential absolutely, but food alone is not
sufficient to prevent death."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "without clean water to drink, disease can
easily claim lives; without proper health care, diseases can
spread unchecked."
</P>
<P>
According to the release, UNICEF has airlifted relief supplies
into the southern regions of Ethiopia, including several tons of
high protein biscuits for children and pregnant women, water cans
for family use, and oral re-hydration salts.
</P>
<P>
The biscuits are particularly valuable because they are ready
to eat and require no preparation or searching for wood and water,
UNICEF noted.
</P>
<P>
Education is also suffering from the drought as children leave
school to help support family incomes. In the Gode region, some
600 kilometers southeast of Addis Ababa, more than one third of
primary schools have shut their doors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
