<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislature to Consider Six Laws in New Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature, the
Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC),
is to hold its 15th session on April 25 to deliberate six draft
laws.
</P>
<P>
The legislative agenda were decided at a meeting today of
chairman and vice-chairmen of the NPC Standing Committee, presided
over by the chairman, Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers on Tuesday tabled the draft amendments to the law on
prevention and control of air pollution, an explanation of an
article of the criminal law, amendments to the law on product
quality, a draft law on farm seeds, and amendments to the customs
law. Each has been reviewed in previous legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
Amendments to the law on the patent rights law will be
submitted to the legislators for a first hearing.
</P>
<P>
A treaty on land borderlines and a consular treaty with Viet
Nam will also be presented to the legislators for deliberation and
ratification, along with a treaty on the dividing point between
the Kyrgyzstan and Kazakhstan, and an additional treaty with
Kyrgyzstan on border issues.
</P>
<P>
The State Council will also deliver a report on the process of
China's entry to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
It was also announced at today's meeting that an addition has
been made to the drafted amendments to the law on the prevention
and control of air pollution, which says that governments at
various levels should "fulfill their due responsibility in
preventing and controlling desertification and sandstorms."
</P>
<P>
The addition was made after Beijing and many other areas of
China were hit by more than seven severe sandstorms and dust
storms this winter, said Wang Weicheng, chairman of the NPC Law
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee also said today it will form special
contingents this year to look into how successfully China's laws
on township enterprises, land management, organization of urban
neighborhood committees and criminal procedures have been enforced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
