<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Water Treatment Plant Opens in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
has formally opened a new water treatment plant in the island's
southern coast, the local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Tersephanou Water Treatment Plant is part of the second
phase of the Southern Conveyor Project, the largest and most
ambitious water development project ever undertaken in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration ceremony Tuesday, Clerides pointed
to the grave problem of water shortage faced by Cyprus, stressing
the importance and need of desalination plants.
</P>
<P>
The new facility actually began operating last December after a
two-month trial run. It can treat 60,000 cubic metres of water a
day and can raise the output to 90,000 cubic meters soon.
</P>
<P>
The plant is an integral part of the Southern Conveyor Project,
which starts at the Kouris Dam in the south and feeds water to
towns along its route to its terminus in Nicosia, the capital.
</P>
<P>
The European Investment Bank and the Kuwait Fund for Arab
Economic Development granted loans totalling 60 percent of the
total cost of the project, which is about 20 million Cyprus pounds
(40 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
With reservoirs in Cyprus 85 percent empty now, and the winter
brought only 61 percent of a "normal" meteorological year's
rainfall, the island remains locked in drought, now for a fifth
straight year, and would thus grow ever more dependent on
desalination plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
