<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Surplus Drops in 1st 2 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines posted a trade
surplus of 485 million U.S. dollars in the first two months of
2000, 1.8 percent lower than the 494 million dollars registered in
the same period of last year, the National Statistics Office said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the office, total trade in goods for the first two
month of this year amounted to 10.753 billion dollars or 9.6
percent higher than 9.807 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Demand for foreign-made merchandise picked up in January and
February as payments rose by 10.2 percent to 5.134 billion dollars
from 4.656 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, exports posted a 9.1 percent year-on-year
gain reporting an aggregate dollar revenue of 5.619 billion
dollars, up from 5.15 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
For February alone, merchandise trade grew by 11.6 percent to 5.
385 billion dollars from 4.826 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports for the month amounted to 2.902 billion dollars,
representing a 13 percent increase from 2.569 billion a year ago,
while expenditures for imported goods increased by 10 percent to 2.
483 billion dollars from 2.257 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus for the month stood at 419 million dollars,
said the office.
</P>
<P>
Led by telecommunication equipment and electrical machinery,
capital goods accounted for 41.2 percent of the country's import
bill in February.
</P>
<P>
Payments for raw materials for the month reached 957.94 billion
dollars, accounting for 38.6 percent of the import bill.
</P>
<P>
Major sources of imports for the month of February were Japan,
the United States, South Korea, Singapore and Taiwan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
