<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Urges Indonesia to Speed-up Legal Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund (
IMF)Wednesday urged the Indonesian government to speed-up legal
reforms process to boost the on-going economic recovery program.
</P>
<P>
It also said that this weekend an IMF technical team would
arrive here to review the implementation of the reforms points
contained in the letter of intent (LoI) before it resume the next
aid package worth 400 million U.S. dollars to the country.
</P>
<P>
"There are points which will influence the on-going economic
recovery program. Firstly, restructuring of banking and debt,
secondly, privatization program, and third is legal reforms," IMF
Senior Representatives in Jakarta John Dodsworth said when
addressing a conference on Indonesian Debt Restructuring and Asset
Sales.
</P>
<P>
Corporate and debt restructuring program will not be successful
without legal reforms, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Because now, (in Indonesia) no one trust the public
institution,including court institution," Dodsworth said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Indonesian Banking Restructuring Agency (IBRA)
, a body under the Finance Ministry, not to concern only with
corporate and debt restructuring and sales asset but also "concern
with how to create healthy banking system."
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Indonesian government should take
immediate measures to curb rampant corruption practices "directly
or indirectly and bringing those it finds guilty to the court."
</P>
<P>
Last month, the IMF delayed to disburse its loan package worth
400 million U.S. dollars due to failure of the Indonesian
government in implementing reforms programs as scheduled by both
sides, the IMF and the government, in April.
</P>
<P>
But later, the IMF was optimistic the Indonesian government
would be able to settle the programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
