<HEADLINE> Kenya Worked Out New Rules for Tea Buyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Tea brokers and buyers in Kenya
will have to register with the Tea Board of Kenya and their
management agents will also be required to register, Agriculture
Minister Chris Obure has said.
</P>
<P>
Obure made the remarks recently when he met with the
stakeholders in the tea industry, saying that the Tea Board of
Kenya will continue to monitor exports through the registration,
the East African Standard newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He explained the the requirements for registration of exports
would be for statistical and planning purposes, adding that with
these changes, there will be no cess levied on tea farms.
</P>
<P>
On tea trade, Obure said, tea packers were required to register
with the tea board and file monthly returns.
</P>
<P>
He noted that when the state-owned Kenya Tea Development
Authority is transformed into an agency, there will be less
government control in its management, saying the transformation
would empower tea farmers in the management, production,
processing and marketing.
</P>
<P>
The government expected that by July this year, the reforms in
the tea industry would make tea growers manage the sector
themselves, thus making the sector more vibrant for offering more
job opportunities and generating more foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is one of major black tea producers in the world. Last
year, it exported 246,000 tons of tea to some 40 countries and
regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
