<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Cyprus Buys Interbank of New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Cyprus has announced a
preliminary agreement for the acquisition of Interbank of New York,
a U.S.-registered bank for a consideration of approximately 43
million U.S. dollars, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition is believed to be a strategic move and part of
the Bank of Cyprus Group's broader policy to expand to overseas
markets where a significant Greek community lives.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations with Interbank started last Friday and the deal was
clinched on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Interbank, set up in 1990, provides services mainly to the Greek
and Cypriot community in New York and has four branches and 52
employees.
</P>
<P>
Its total assets amount to 173 million dollars, customer
deposits 156 million dollars, and total advances 115 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition of Interbank is in accordance with the Bank of
Cyprus Group's policy for the effective utilization of the new
capital which will be raised through a public offering in Greece
for the listing of the Bank of Cyprus shares on the Athens Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Usually relying on its own resources to build a presence
overseas, this is only the second time in the 100-year history of
the Bank of Cyprus that it has acquired another bank. It took over
the Cyprus activities of Standard Chartered Bank in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is contingent on approval from the Central Bank of
Cyprus and the U.S. authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
