<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli Security Cabinet decided Tuesday not to challenge
the Supreme Court's decision to release 13 Lebanese hostages being
held in Israel as "bargaining chips" for the return of missing
Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
However, the release, scheduled for Wednesday, will be delayed
until the court considers a petition against the release submitted
by the family of missing Israel Air Force navigator Ron Arad
Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The security cabinet is resolved to concentrate its efforts on
speedily moving to ensure that two other, more prominent detainees,
Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid of Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas and
Mustafa Dirani of Amal militia, not be allowed to go free.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Katyusha rocket fire struck a settlement in the Western
Galilee Tuesday afternoon. The rockets damaged an electricity
transformer, causing a blackout in the region for several hours.
Two women were treated after complaining of illness as a result of
the blasts.
</P>
<P>
Though the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) Northern Command did not
ask local residents to take cover in bomb shelters, officers
estimated Tuesday that the Katyusha attack against Israeli
civilians was deliberate and categorized it as being "very grave."
</P>
<P>
The strike came at the peak of a day of heavy skirmishing in
southern Lebanon that left one Syrian construction worker dead and
five people injured, including two IDF soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The horde of Israeli fans that have descended on Salonika,
Greece exulted in victory Tuesday night after Israel's Maccabi Tel
Aviv crushed Barcelona of Spain by 65-51 to move into the European
Champions League basketball final.
</P>
<P>
The victory is the first time in 11 years. If Maccabi Tel Aviv
defeats another finalist Panathinaikos of Greece in the final on
Thursday night, they will kiss the championship cup for the first
time since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Israelis came without tickets and had to watch the
game on large screen TV in pubs along the city's boardwalk. Others
managed to buy tickets from Spaniards and Greeks for as much as 1,
500 U.S. dollars apiece.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad wants a resumption of peace
talks as soon as possible and has a genuine desire for peace,
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The president has told me that he wanted peace talks to resume
as soon as possible," said Chretien, who met with Assad for 90
minutes.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at the Damascus airport before leaving for
Saudi Arabia that he was impressed by the Syrian president's desire
and commitment to peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
