<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Official Cash Rate Up to 6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's central bank,
the Reserve Bank, Wednesday increased the Official Cash Rate (OCR)
from 5.75 percent to 6 percent as part of a series of moves
designed to stop inflation spreading.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark rate determines the cost of borrowing and
influences returns on deposits.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement, Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash said the
New Zealand economy has now been growing robustly for almost two
years and the risks of rising inflation are gradually increasing.
</P>
<P>
"Firmer monitory conditions will be needed if we are to give
ourselves the best chance of solid growth continuing without
inflation problems emerging," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Brash raised the OCR regardless of acting Prime Minister Jim
Anderton publicly pleading with him not to do so.
</P>
<P>
Anderton warned that when interest rates rise, exchange rates
rise."That makes for weaker competitiveness in the export sector
which discourages exporters and encourages importing. And that of
course just exacerbates the balance of payments deficit."
</P>
<P>
Anderton hoped that Brash would "leave interest rates unchanged
".
</P>
<P>
But under the Reserve Bank Act of New Zealand, the interest
rate is a matter of the Governor's judgment and the Governor is
accountable for it in terms of the consequences that follow.
</P>
<P>
Brash has been gradually tightening the screws on the economy
over the past six months. He raised the OCR in November, January
and March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 45 Bodies Recovered From Crashed Philippine Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Rescuers have recovered 45 bodies
from the crash site of Air Philippines Flight 54l which crashed
Wednesday morning in the southern Philippines with more than 120
passengers and crew members on board.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from the crash site on Samal Island in
Danao del Norte province said no survivor has been found so far.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 737-200 with 123 passengers and 6 crew members on
board crashed at around 07:05 (23:05 GMT,Tuesday) in Mount
Camanlangan of Samal Island some 1,000 kilometers south of Manila.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated passenger plane left the Philippine capital of
Manila at around 05:20 (21:20 GMT, Tuesday) and was expected to
reach Davao City at 06:45 (22:45 GMT, Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
Air and land rescue recovery teams that arrived more than an
hour after the disaster in the rugged highland of the island said
the aircraft was in total wreck while the passengers and crew were
badly mangled.
</P>
<P>
Villagers said they heard two loud explosions as soon as the
aircraft zoomed down across coconut grove in the island some 8
kilometers east of the Davao International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada expressed sorrow over the
early morning crash and ordered concerned agencies to investigate
the tragedy and immediately provide assistance to relatives of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
Secretaries Vicente Rivera of the Department of Transportation
and Communications and Orlando Mercado of the Department of
National Defense went to the crash site to investigate the
accident and oversee search and rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
A welfare center to serve the kins of the crash victims of the
ill-fated plane has been established in Davao City.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the management of Air Philippines has also
established a holding area in the same city to likewise serve the
needs of the kins of the victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
