<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean White Farmers Eye Zambia for Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Some white farmers in neighboring
Zimbabwe are eyeing Zambia for investment and have started making
inquiries about the land policy of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Daily Mail newspaper Wednesday quoted President of
Zambia National Farmers Union (ZNFU) Ajay Vashee as saying here on
Tuesday that the inquiries include the market policy.
</P>
<P>
According to Vashee, his union will welcome good farmers from
Zimbabwe who are going to invest in the country but not those who
will only want to run away from paying back loans.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean farmers have been told about Zambia's
liberalized market and present government-respected title to land,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vashee urged the Zimbabwean government to resolve
the conflict over land, saying it will affect investor confidence
in southern African region if the situation is allowed to
continue.
</P>
<P>
Most investors outside Africa would avoid the region because
they do not know that Zimbabwe is just a country in southern
Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have no pressures on land in Zambia. We will welcome good
Zimbabwean white farmers who wish to invest in Zambia. We have
good land and marketing policies here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe Tuesday said that
his government was determined to resolve the land issue once and
for all.
</P>
<P>
In his national address to mark 20 years of independence,
Mugabe said he could understand the frustration of the war
veterans and the pressures faced by white commercial farmers in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe will soon send a high-powered delegation to London for
talks with the British government on the land issue.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 white-owned farms have so far been occupied by war
veterans since they launched the invasion almost two months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
