<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Endorses Insurance Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has addressed the political and
commercial risk associated with Africa in the Free Trade Area
(FTA) by endorsing the establishment of the African Trade
Insurance Agency.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made at the just-ended fourth meeting of the
COMESA committee on legal affairs held in Lusaka to increase the
availability of financial resources for investments and other
productive activities, the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It also aims to reduce the cost of trade finance in Africa by
mitigating the political and commercial risks associated with the
continent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to COMESA Clearing House consultant Mahmood Mansoor,
seven COMESA members, namely, Burundi, Rwanda, Kenya, Uganda,
Tanzania, Malawi and Zambia, endorsed the agency while Zimbabwe
and Mozambique are still deciding on whether or not to join the
scheme.
</P>
<P>
The scheme has been implemented and supported by the World
Bank, which will be providing the International Development
Association eligible states with soft loans, Mansoor said.
</P>
<P>
He said the scheme, which will be in effect within a year of
the operation of the FTA, is to facilitate, encourage and develop
the provision of insurance and reinsurance, and other financial
instruments and services for the purpose of trade and other
productive activities in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
