<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Leading Astronomical Observatories Connected on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Astronomers worldwide will be
able to have access to 11 world-leading astronomical observatories
through Internet2 networks.
</P>
<P>
Internet2, a consortium led by 170 U.S. universities to
accelerate the creation of tomorrow's Internet, said Tuesday that
it has connected 11 of the world's leading astronomical
observatories to its high-performance networks via the Mauna Kea
Observatories Communication Network.
</P>
<P>
There are educational benefits to the new link as well,
according to the consortium.
</P>
<P>
The high-performance connection will allow the observatories to
share more of their findings with the public through techniques
such as virtual observatory tours and live video from Mauna Kea to
museums, planetaria and classrooms worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The University of Hawaii, who took part in the efforts to
facilitate the connection, will develop a new Mauna Kea Astronomy
Educational Center in its Research Park, which will utilize the
high-performance connection to the observatories along with a
planetarium, video conferencing and instructional facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
