<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Customs Seize More Smuggled Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Customs officials in south
China's Guangdong Province, neighboring Hong Kong and Macao,
seized 127 million yuan (15 million U.S. dollars) worth of
smuggled goods in the first quarter this year, 91 percent more
than in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
These goods ranged from cars, motorcycles, refined oil products,
and edible oil to pirated compact discs and roll films, a customs
official said today.
</P>
<P>
To curb smuggling via the sea, customs has enhanced their
patrols, which now operate 24 hours a day. These efforts helped
foil 156 smuggling attempts and retrieve 38 million yuan (4.5
million U.S. dollars) during the period.
</P>
<P>
Customs officials have also intensified their fight against the
smuggling of pornographic publications, drugs, cultural relics,
guns and ammunition, and fake foreign currencies, the official
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
