<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Civilization History in South China Pushed Earlier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A three-year long archeological
excavation in Xiaojin Village in southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region has helped bring forward the local civilization
history by more than 4,000 years.
</P>
<P>
Yan Wenming, a professor with the Beijing University, affirmed
that the excavation proves that the Xiaojin Culture is a native
rather than an affiliation moved from other parts of the country
as formerly thought by most Chinese archeologists.
</P>
<P>
The site, some 100 km away from the famous scenic city of
Guilin, is encompassed by mountains. Large amounts of primitive
production instruments and utility devises belonged to the late
Neolithic Age were unearthed since the excavation was carried out
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archeologists announced here that they had to reassess
the origin of the local history, which represents the typical
southern China primitive culture. They now believe that primitive
tribes inhabited in the region as early as 4,000-5,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Stocks of carbonized rice unearthed in the pit suggest the
level of primitive farming. Archeologists can also assessed the
standard of weaving and aesthetic based on the finds of stone
spinning wheels and stone bracelets.
</P>
<P>
Yan said that the archeological team has figured out the
chronic changes from the one meter deep relic layer, which is
rarely distinguishable.
</P>
<P>
They assumed that a primitive community consisted of some 60
members lived here for a pretty long period. They mainly lived on
farming and hunting.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still a mystery whether the tribe was a
matriarchy or a patriarchy, and where it was gone or how it
disappeared, Yan said. Intensive studies are now under way for all
the answers.
</P>
<P>
The South China Culture has been generally considered to have
come into shape much later than that in the north. But research of
some archeological finds in recent years are likely to push
forward the history of the former, which is still little known, as
observed by more Chinese archeologists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Welfare Dependency Blamed for High Mortality Among Australian Aboriginals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Australian Aboriginal Affairs
Minister John Herron blamed Wednesday the high death rate in the
400,000 indigenous population on a culture of welfare dependency,
the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
According to figures issued recently by the Australian Bureau
of Statistics, 53 percent of indigenous men who died between 1995
and 1997 and 41 percent of women, were aged under 50 comparing
with just 13 percent of all male deaths and seven percent of all
female deaths under the age of 50 in Australia in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Earlier statistics showed that the average life expectancy of
the Aboriginals is about 20 years lower than non-Aboriginals.
Heart disease, injury, respiratory disease, cancer and diabetes
were the main causes of their death.
</P>
<P>
Herron said these diseases were caused by unhealthy lifestyles
exacerbated by alcohol and cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
"One of the big problems we've got today is welfare dependency,
" Herron told journalists. "Over the past 30 years we've tended to
make Aboriginal people welfare dependent -- all good intentioned
and all that -- but as they tell me they've got sit-down money,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
the Australian government has earmarked around 2 billion
Australian dollars (1.18 billion U.S. dollars) for Aboriginal
communities every year but failed to pull them out from the poor
economic and health conditions.
</P>
<P>
"They don't want sit-down money, they want jobs, they want a
roof over their head, they want education, they want everything
else that every other Australian is entitled to have," the
minister stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Kids Administered Vitamin A </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 19 (Xinhua) -- About 2.78 million Nepali
children aged six-month-old to six-year-old were administered
vitamin A capsules in a two-day national vitamin A program that
ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The program which was carried out twice a year by the Ministry
of Health aimed at imparting the knowledge about the importance of
vitamin A which is not sufficient in the diet of Nepalese people.
</P>
<P>
Some 35,000 women volunteers who helped with the program also
made efforts in teaching people to make good use of natural
sources of vitamin A such as green vegetable, fruits, fishes, eggs
and breast feeding to babies.
</P>
<P>
Lack of vitamin A has caused high child mortality rate and
pervasive eye diseases such as cataract and glaucoma in Nepal,
especially in the country's rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
