<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Reports 37 Percent Profits For First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp., the world's
largest microprocessor maker, said Tuesday that its first-quarter
net income rose 37 percent, including acquisition-related charges,
according to reports from the company.
</P>
<P>
The Santa Clara, California-based chip maker reported net
income of 2.7 billion U.S. dollars, or 78 cents a share, including
acquisition-related charges and a 17 cents tax benefit gain, from
2 billion dollars, or 57 cents a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Excluding acquisition-related costs, Intel reported net income
of 3.1 billion dollars, or 88 cents a share, which included 17
cents a share from tax benefits.
</P>
<P>
Revenues rose to 8.0 billion dollars, up from 7.1 billion
dollars in the first quarter of 1999, with PC sales stronger than
expected in the traditionally sluggish quarter that follows the
Christmas shopping season.
</P>
<P>
Sequentially, revenues in the latest quarter were down 2
percent from the prior fourth quarter, as the company had
predicted in January, due to seasonality.
</P>
<P>
"Demand was stronger in the quarter -- across all product lines
-- than we had anticipated," said Andy Bryant, Intel's chief
financial officer. "It was microprocessors, chipsets, flash (
memory chips)... Demand was stronger than anticipated and as a
result we did not meet all the demand in the quarter. If we had
had more parts, we could have shipped them."
</P>
<P>
Intel also said it expected second quarter revenues to come in
about even with the first quarter and that product supply would
continue to be tight in the current second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, among the 150 or so Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies
that had already reported their latest results by Tuesday
afternoon, 71 percent of them had beaten analyst profit forecasts
for the first three months of the year, according to First Call/
Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
The remaining two-thirds of the 500 major companies are due to
report their first-quarter profits and revenues over the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the fright of recent days, the earnings news thus
far has been soothing, if not encouraging. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
