<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Third Economic Development Plan (2000-2005) is
based on attracting foreign investments, boosting foreign trade,
and also technical and economic cooperation with other countries,
officials said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iran has to reach an economic growth rate of 6 percent in the
five years to solve the problem of unemployment, currently as high
as 16 percent, according to Masoud Nili, deputy director of
economic affairs at the Plan and Budget Organization. (BC-Iran-
Economic Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- The geological and exploration studies performed
in Rosia Montana-Bucium area of western Romania made obvious the
existence of some resources of eight million gold ounces, the
largest gold deposits ever discovered in Europe, the Gabriel
Resources Ltd. Company's president Frank Timis announced here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Drilling-exploration studies in Rosia Montana-Bucium area were
performed by Rosia Montana Gold Corporation joint venture and were
worth 20 million U.S. dollars. They were followed by a re-
feasibility study achieved by an American company. (BC-Romania-
Gold)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The South Korean government has decided to use pension
and other long-term funds to help stabilize the stock market when
necessary.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a governmental meeting which focused
on discussion of measures to stabilize the stock market.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the government also decided to restrict larger
shareholders of KOSDAQ-listed companies from selling shares over
the short-term. (BC-SKorea-Stock)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Germany has decided to cancel the total debt
valued at 62.7 million U.S. dollars owed by Tanzania, the African
newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian Minister for Finance Daniel Yona was quoted as
saying on Monday that Germany's decision is in line with the Paris
Club decision last week to cancel Tanzania's 1.88 billion U.S.
dollars debt. (BC-Tanzania-Debt) 
