<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia Embarking on Transition to K-Economy (1)  By Wu Dingbao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's National Congress
for Youths on K-Economy (knowledge-based economy) concluded
Tuesday with the consensus that the country and its people should
leapfrog into the knowledge economy.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference aimed at wooing youths to get involved
in K-economy was one of a series of forums to be held to gather
feedback and ideas from the people towards realizing the K-economy,
as the Malaysian government is making great efforts to speed up
the transition of the economy from present production-based to
knowledge-based.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the government is in the process of drafting the
first National Master Plan on the country's K-economy, which is
expected to be completed by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Deputy Finance Minister Chan Kong Choy disclosed
last month that a national strategic plan identifying key sectors
in the Master Plan would be announced in June this year.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the initiatives to steer Malaysia towards K-economy
earlier this month, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said the vital
measures that need to be taken under the Master Plan would be
incorporated in the 2001 budget to be presented in October.
</P>
<P>
He said a series of concrete plans of action in key strategic
areas will be completed within one year while the whole process of
national consultation and national mobilization will be completed
in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The transition of the economy from production-based to
knowledge-based implies that the manufacturing sector, which
accounts for more than one third of the gross domestic product (
GDP) of the country, would face new challenges including
advancements in Information and communications technology (ICT).
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the manufacturing sector, which will continue to
assume an important role in the K-economy, has been urged to
adjust to the rapid change of pace to commit itself for the
enhancement of knowledge in all aspects of economic activity.
</P>
<P>
Spurred by the drive towards to the K-economy, the local
information technology (IT) market was projected to expand fast at
an average annual growth rate of more than 13 percent from now to
2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Embarking on Transition to K-Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the latest survey findings by research firm
International Data Corp (IDC), the local IT market is projected to
record a growth of 18.6 percent this year with IT spending hitting
6.76 billion ringgit (1.778 billion U.S. dollars) compared with
the estimated 5.7 billion ringgit (1.5 billion dollars) in 1999
and some 5 billion ringgit (1.315 billion dollars) in 1998, and by
2004, the value of IT spending on the local market is estimated to
be worth 10.87 billion ringgit (2.86 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
This year alone, there will be 1.89 million Internet users in
Malaysia with 1.06 million Internet devices deployed, the research
firm said.
</P>
<P>
However, the implementation of the K-economy concept is not
confined to information technology and communications but also
covers other sectors including education and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that in transforming to K-Economy, there exists a
digital gap between areas equipped with basic amenities for
electricity, telephone lines, computers and the Internet and those
areas which are not so well equipped, the Malaysian government
together with the private sector are taking steps to bring
communications facilities and electric power to the people in
efforts to reduce the digital gap.
</P>
<P>
For example, the number of telephones for every 100 residents
in Malaysia in 1995 was 16.6 and the ratio was expected to
increase to 23.3 this year.
</P>
<P>
In terms of electricity supply, Malaysia has succeeded in
providing coverage in Peninsular Malaysia to 100 percent, while
coverage for Sarawak and Sabah, the two states in East Malaysia,
is 80 percent and 75 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
To accelerate the transformation to K-economy, Malaysia's
strategies are placing greater emphasis on enhancing the nation's
knowledge reservoir to increase the levels of efficiency,
productivity and human resources skills to meet the demands of
global market.
</P>
<P>
The government has introduced IT in primary and secondary
schools to produce a new generation of creative and innovative IT-
literate Malaysians to meet the manpower needs of the nation in
the fields of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
To this end, more than 1,200 teachers have been trained to
conduct the computer-in-education program in schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
