<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Web-Enabled Community Expects Explosive E-Commerce Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. companies dealing with
the Internet transaction predict in a Tuesday's survey an
explosive e-commerce growth, migration to next-generation
solutions and a major shift in revenue sources.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by U.S. management consulting firm A.T.
Kearney, offers the first comprehensive look at the present state
and future prospects of business-to-business (B2B) e-commerce
within this Web-enabled community. The findings are based on 85
interviews with these "net market makers" serving 10 industries.
</P>
<P>
All companies interviewed said that they expect explosive
revenue growth, and more than 80 percent forecast annual growth
rate in their employees bases of more than 200 percent over the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
"This optimism is not unwarranted," Kearney said, commenting on
the study results. "Buyers and sellers alike are struggling with
the high total cost of transactions, fragmented and multi-layered
supply chains, inefficient purchasing processes and poor
communications that characterize today's traditional market place.
The e-commerce solutions address those concerns and are being
sought after by industries across the board."
</P>
<P>
The study shows that as trading models become more advanced in
response to market demand, commerce solutions will have to evolve
to support buyer and seller needs. In fact, the companies with "
dynamic trading capabilities" through auction and liquid exchanges
said that they are looking for next-generation solutions. And
those that lack dynamic trading indicated that they plan to add
auction and exchange capabilities.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, net market makers predict a major
shift in revenue sources from transaction fees to value-added
services such as content management, logistics, escrow and payment
services, inventory management, risk management and order
fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
Right now, 87 percent of the companies rely on transaction fees
as their primary source of revenue, with only 10 percent
generating revenue from value-added services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
