<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Major Japanese Banks Announce Alliance Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi (BTM)
and Mitsubishi Trust &AMP; Banking Corp. said Wednesday they have
agreed to integrate their management under a joint holding company
in April 2001.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Trust Bank and Tokyo Trust Bank, both BTM subsidiaries,
will also join the alliance, the banks said.
</P>
<P>
The integration will create the world's fifth largest and Japan
's fourth biggest banking group by assets. BTM and Mitsubishi
Trust held 85.19 trillion yen (815.2 billion dollars) in combined
assets as of September 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed integration, BTM and Mitsubishi Trust will
establish a joint holding company, with two chief executive
officers coming from each of the two banks.
</P>
<P>
Once integrated, BTM will focus on conventional banking such as
lending and deposit-taking, while Mitsubishi Trust will conduct
mainly asset trust and management, the banks said.
</P>
<P>
The alliance will be the first in Japan involving a trust bank
and a major commercial bank with a nationwide branch network.
</P>
<P>
The integration would give the final finish to ongoing plans to
reconfigure Japan's nine "city" banks into four major banking
groups, the Mizuho Financial Group, the Sanwa-Tokai-Asahi group,
the Sumitomo-Sakura group and finally the BTM-led group.
</P>
<P>
The Mizuho Financial Group, consisting of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank,
Fuji Bank and the Industrial Bank of Japan, will be formed at the
end of September.
</P>
<P>
The Sanwa-Tokai-Asahi camp will be established in April 2001 by
Sanwa Bank, Tokai Bank and Asahi Bank.
</P>
<P>
The planned Sumitomo-Sakura alliance, which will have Sumitomo
Bank and Sakura Bank, will be created by April 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
