<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Reports Better-Than-Expected Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 18 (Xinhua) -- International Business
Machines Corp. (IBM) Tuesday reported a three-percent increase in
first-quarter profit, easily beating Wall Street estimates,
according to reports from the company.
</P>
<P>
The world's leading computer company earned 1.52 billion
dollars, or 83 cents a share, in the three months ending in March,
up from 1.47 billion dollars, or 78 cents per share, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The results beat the 78-cent per share First Call consensus
estimate. However, revenue fell 5 percent to 19.3 billion dollars
from 20.3 billion dollars in the year-earlier quarter.
</P>
<P>
IBM, like other computer manufacturers, has been hurt by
weakness in corporate spending on new computers in the first few
months after the Year 2000 date change, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Hardware revenue dropped by 12 percent to 7.7 billion dollars,
as sales of personal computers and other products declined.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from IBM Global Services totaled 7.6 billion dollars,
flat over the year-earlier period amid the sale of the IBM Global
Network last year to AT&AMP;T Corp. and a severe year-over-year drop
in Y2K-related service revenue. Software revenue was also flat at
2.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The first quarter was a difficult transitional quarter," Chief
Financial Officer John Joyce said in a conference call with
analysts. But "our business portfolio is improved and the pipeline
of opportunity has started to build."
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, among the 150 or so Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies
that had already reported their latest results by Tuesday
afternoon, 71 percent of them had beaten analyst profit forecasts
for the first three months of the year, according to First Call/
Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
The remaining two-thirds of the 500 S&AMP;P companies are due to
report their first-quarter profits and revenues over the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the fright of recent days, analysts say, the
earnings news so far has been soothing, if not encouraging.
</P>
</TEXT>
