<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Hospitals, More Doctors in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released by China's
Ministry of Health (MOH) today show a drop in the number of
medical institutes, a slow growth in the ranks of medical
personnel, and imbalanced development among urban and rural health
care services.
</P>
<P>
China had a total of 311,000 hospitals, clinics, disease
prevention agencies, health care centers, research institutes, and
medical schools and colleges by the end of 1999, compared with 314,
100 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Some 5.57 million people worked in these institutions, a rise
of about 35,000 over 1998.
</P>
<P>
The MOH report shows that 239 hospital beds, 102 nurses, and
167 doctors were available for every 100,000 Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
A health care network composed of medical facilities at the
county, township, and village levels now covers some 90 percent of
China's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
However, the development of health care services in cities and
rural areas remains imbalanced due to the investment gap.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 80 percent of the health care budget has been
earmarked for cities, with some 80 percent of this funding going
to major urban hospitals. The growth of basic health care for
rural residents, or 69 percent of the total population, remains
slow due to inadequate investment, according to a MOH official.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals and clinics nationwide accepted about 2.08 billion
patient visits last year, and about 50 million people were
hospitalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
