<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Tighten Liquidity to Stabilize Rupiah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to help stabilize the
weakening rupiah, Bank Indonesia, the Indonesian central bank,
will continue to tighten domestic liquidity conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to Bank Indonesia's Deputy Director of Economic and
Monetary Research Halim Alamsyah, the bank aims at bringing down
the size of base money to below April's 86 trillion rupiah (about
11.4 billion U.S. dollar) target by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
"We'll try to control the monetary condition more carefully ...
we'll adopt a tight bias (policy). But this doesn't mean that we'
re going to raise interest rates," he was quoted by the Jakarta
Post Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Halim explained that the central bank's tighter liquidity
measure did not have to be accompanied by higher interest rates
because domestic banks currently had excessive liquidity, enabling
them to purchase Bank Indonesia's notes at the current low
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
He said the size of the base money over the past couple of
weeks was already about 90 trillion rupiah (about 12 billion U.S.
dollars), or above the target.
</P>
<P>
"So we tend to be more tight," he said, adding that the policy
was taken at the recent central bank board of governors meeting.
</P>
<P>
Halim was responding to the current weakening of the value of
the rupiah against the U.S. dollar. The rupiah has been indirectly
affected by the bearish sentiment in the world stock market.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah closed lower on Tuesday at 7,733 rupiah against the
U.S. dollar from 7,675 rupiah previously.
</P>
<P>
The government and the central bank has targeted the rupiah to
be trading at 7,000 rupiah per U.S. dollar this year.
</P>
<P>
However, Halim said the current weakening of the rupiah was not
yet worrying. "The market still thinks that this (weakening) is
temporary," he said.
</P>
<P>
The important thing for the central bank is to make sure the
weakening of the rupiah does not threaten its inflation target for
this year, according to the bank official.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's underline inflation target for this year is
3 to 5 percent, or 5 to 7 percent if the planned increased in fuel
prices is taken into account. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0304 </DOCNO>
