<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riots Continue in Central Sulawesi, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Despite the heavy presence of
security personnel, sectarian riots continued sporadically in the
Poso city, Indonesia's Central Sulawesi province, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here Wednesday, smoke was seen
billowing from buildings across the paralyzed town, about 2,000
kilometers northeast of Jakarta. Markets and shops were closed as
fearful residents stayed indoors.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 people whose homes were burned down in the unrest have
been evacuated. Many of them were sheltered at local military
dormitory and offices.
</P>
<P>
In the flight, the reports said, many of the people brought
nothing but the clothes they were wearing.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the Wirabuana Military Command overseeing
Sulawesi Maj. Joko Warsito said at least 600 reinforcements were
sent to the area.
</P>
<P>
"We've just deployed another 200 troops from the Infantry
Battalion 711 in addition to more than 100 reinforcements sent
there soon after the riots exploded. We just don't want the unrest
to develop on a bigger scale," he was quoted by the Jakarta Post
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The conflict in Poso was sparked by a fight between teenagers
at the bus terminal on Sunday, which grew into clashes between
residents from Lambogia and Kayamanya villages.
</P>
<P>
Joko said Poso was vulnerable to sectarian riots. Residents
living in the northern area clashed many times with those in the
south.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Post quoted military and political observers as
saying that Sulawesi could descent into communal violence after
the prolonged sectarian strife in the neighboring Maluku, which
has claimed thousands of lives since it broke out in January 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
