<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Organic Tea Village is Cancer-free (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Zhangshan Village may be even
more well-known in Europe than in China: the village now accounts
for 60 percent of the organic tea products on the European Union
market.
</P>
<P>
Zhangshan, a small village in Wuyuan County of East China's
Jiangxi Province, is located in Dazhangshan Mountains 900 meters
above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Situated on the highest peak of Dazhangshan, Zhangshan is
surrounded by trees and tea plantations, with a small river
running through.
</P>
<P>
With ideal climate and peculiar fertile soil, the village had
for generations produced tribute tea for Chinese emperors in the
past, said village head Wang Qiangtian.
</P>
<P>
The village has 145 households with 577 persons, and most of
them work on tea plantations.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yangqin, a local medical worker who has served the
villagers for more than 20 years, said definitely that according
to the village's medical treatment records, there has never been
any cancer patient among Zhangshan residents, and 80 percent of
elderly people died of no illness.
</P>
<P>
Average life expectancy is 73 years for all villagers and 78
for females, and there are now a dozen of octogenarians or even
centenarians.
</P>
<P>
Wang the medical worker attributed the good health and
longevity of villagers to the surrounding environment and the
healthy foods villagers eat.
</P>
<P>
Zhangshan Village has no industries. Villagers never use
pesticide in planting tea and vegetables, and they never use
manufactured fodder in raising pigs and chickens.
</P>
<P>
Wang the village head said most of the villagers love the life
there. "Although there is no disco and Internet, young people are
still dressed in fashionable styles," Wang added.
</P>
<P>
He said less than 5 percent of villagers have left the village
to work in other places in Jiangxi or other provinces in China.
</P>
<P>
However, the village is not isolated. More and more outsiders
including foreigners are visiting Zhangshan.
</P>
<P>
Most visitors come to the village to enjoy the beautiful scenes
and historical sites, for archeologists believe the village has
some of the best-preserved ancient houses in the country. But
among the foreigners some are tea traders from Europe who come for
the village's leading product -- Dazhangshan Mountain Tea.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the village has regained its glory as
a famous tea producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Centenarians in Scenic Spot of Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- There are more centenarians in
the Dai Autonomous Prefecture of Xishuangbanna, a scenic spot in
southwest China's Yunnan province that attracts some two million
tourists every year.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by the Yunnan Health Department,
the proportion of centenarians in Xishuangbanna's total population
is higher than that of Yunnan Province and the whole country.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, there were 37 centenarians among its
population of 830,000, meaning there were 44 centenarians among
one million people, compared to a national average of 5.67 and the
provincial average of 7.2.
</P>
<P>
Local heath officials attributed their longevity to good
nutrition, clean environment and better medical facilities in the
tropical rain forest area.
</P>
<P>
But they pointed out that this was not the case 40 years ago,
when tropical epidemics were rampant in the area and the average
life expectancy at that time was not older than 34.
</P>
<P>
After New China was born in 1949, the Central Government has
sent many medical teams to the area to treat ethnic people and
train local doctors, they added.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, there were 132 hospitals and other medical facilities
in the resort, compared to only 6 hospitals in 1950s, they noted
</P>
<P>
Now the average life expectancy of Xishuangbanna people is 66
years old and the number of people aged 70 and above has exceeded
one thousand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Organic Tea Village is Cancer-free (2)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1996, the Dazhangshan Mountain Tea became the first among
the country's hundreds of varieties of tea to win the "AA" mark
for organic food, awarded by the China Organic Food Development
Center.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the organic food monitoring and testing agency of the
European Union (EU) carried out an on-the-spot examination and
proved that the Dazhangshan Mountain Tea is completely free of
pesticide.
</P>
<P>
The certification gives the Dazhangshan Mountain Tea a permit
to enter markets of 140 countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, villager Yu Lianfang brought self-made Dazhangshan
Mountain Tea to the '99 Kunming World Horticulture Expo to compete
with over 140 other tea products. The tea won one of the two gold
medals for tea products.
</P>
<P>
Hong Peng, chairman of the Organic Product Group Company of
Wuyuan County, disclosed that 60 percent of the organic tea on the
EU market is the Dazhangshan Mountain Tea. Its export volume rose
from 1 ton in 1997 to 600 tons in 1999.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, orders from EU nations for Dazhangshan
Mountain Tea have amounted to 1,200 tons.
</P>
<P>
Wuyuan County is one of China's first 50 counties designated
for developing ecology-friendly agriculture. The county has closed
down all the paper-making mills, and helped most of local farmers
to shift from firewood to biogas or using fuel-efficient stoves
for cooking.
</P>
<P>
Chen Shupeng, an academician with the China Academy of Sciences,
and a group of scientists recently made an inspection tour of
Jiangxi, and they concluded that the environments of many
localities in the province are similar to that of Zhangshan
Village. They believe Jiangxi has the potential to establish
China's first ecology-friendly regional economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
