<HEADLINE> Private Firms Urged to Help the Poor in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- China encourages private
entrepreneurs to continue to focus on eliminating poverty in the
western and central provinces, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"The country's strategic shift to the western areas has offered
investors a rare opportunity," said Jing Shuping, president of All-
China Federation of Industry and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The Glorious Program, initiated by 10 private entrepreneurs six
years ago, aims to provide financing for China's poverty-stricken
central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that 3,508 private entrepreneurs has spent 10.521
billion yuan (1.3 billion U.S. dollars) on 3,829 projects of the
program by the end of last year, and the program was mainly
carried out for the industrialization and development of
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
They have offered jobs to 761,500 people and provided training
to 733,600 people. A total of 1.9 million people have been
relieved from poverty, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang urged private entrepreneurs to make careful plans to
promote the steady progress of the program.
</P>
<P>
"The program has played an important role in eliminating
poverty and maintaining social stability because private
entrepreneurs have integrated their capital, information,
management and technology with the natural resources and labor of
the poor regions," the paper quoted Wang Zhaoguo, director of the
CPC United Front Work Department as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wang's department and Jiang's federation are both sponsors for
the program.  
</P>
