<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Conservatives Demand Punishing Reformists for Attending Berlin Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Over 140 members of the outgoing
conservative-dominated Iranian Majlis (parliament) on Wednesday
called on the judiciary to put on trial the Iranian reformists who
attended the Berlin conference last week on Iran.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the hard-line parliamentarians condemned those
who took part in the conference "where the counter-revolutionaries
had insulted the Iranian nation," the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
They accused the reformists in the Berlin conference of
advocating United States-style reforms in Iran, which the supreme
leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei strongly rejected in a speech on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The conference was held by the Heinrich Boell Foundation on Iran
after the February Iranian parliamentary elections in which
reformists won an overwhelming victory over the powerful
conservatives, who control most of the country's sensitive organs.
</P>
<P>
Iran's conservative-dominated state-run television on Tuesday
night showed parts of the conference, particularly a disruption by
members of outlawed Mujaheddin Khalq Organization (MKO) who accused
the Iranian government of "crimes and human rights violations" in
Iran since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The conference organizer had invited some close allies and
supporters of President Mohammad Khatami, including reformist
cleric Yussefi Eshkevari and reformist journalist Akbar Ganji.
</P>
<P>
The participants expressed support for Khatami's reforms and
condemned press censorship and political repression in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran's main reformist party the Islamic Iran Participation Front
(IIPF) on Wednesday accused the state television of trying to stop
the new reformist-dominated parliament from meeting and undermining
Khatami's reform programs.
</P>
<P>
The IIPF, headed by Mohammad Reza Khatami, the president's
younger brother and the top winner in the February polling in
Tehran, said that broadcasting the selective parts of the
conference on the national television is a provocative act serving
only factional interests.
</P>
<P>
The broadcast was also strongly condemned as "an insult to
Islamic sanctities" by Khatami's representative on the state radio
and television, Deputy Foreign Minister Mohsen Aminzadeh.
</P>
<P>
Aminzadeh warned that the management of the television should
bear the responsibility for the consequences of the screening.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been clouded by political tension since the
parliamentary elections which ended a long-time conservative
majority in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The powerful conservatives, unwilling to accept the humiliating
defeat, have taken strong measures to counter the reformist
campaign, including summoning reformist journalists to courts and
overturning by force part of the election results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
