<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ready to Cooperate With Panama in Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- American Ambassador in Panama
Simon Ferro said Wednesday that his country has always been
interested in cooperating with Panamanian authorities in relation
to the national security project.
</P>
<P>
"We have always been in the best disposition to help Panama,
specially in the area we know. I believe that there are no two
countries in the world that know each other as good as Panama and
the United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ferro said that it is still premature to talk about what sort
of cooperation there will be between both countries, for the
Panamanian government must first finish the details of the
Security Strategic Plan, known now as the Foundations of the
Panamanian Security Strategies.
</P>
<P>
"After the government approves the project, then we will be
able to sit, talk and see what we can do," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador considers that it is prudent that Panama
promotes a national and international security plan to safeguard
its territory.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Interior and Justice Minister Winston
Spadafora said that the national government is in the final stage
in the elaboration of the national security project, which has
been modified with the participation of the political parties and
civil society.
</P>
<P>
The current name of the National Security Strategic Plan,
presented last November, was adopted at the suggestion of the
commission of the opposition Democratic Revolutionary Party (PRD).
</P>
<P>
Spadafora added that the definitive text of the strategic
project will be revealed to public opinion after Easter Week.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian minister said that despite new modifications,
the efficient coordination between the National Police, the
National Maritime Service, the National Air Service, the
Institutional Protection Service, and the Civil Protection
National System will be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Spadafora said that the security project will take into account
points of view from different countries. "It would be as absurd
for Panama as for any other country not to accept advice from any
other nation with more advanced technology," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that advice from other countries is not a synonym of
the government selling sovereignty. "The agreements will be
related, only to information exchange."
</P>
<P>
The three elements contemplated in the original security plan
are the Authority of the Panama Canal, the democratic system and
its preservation, and the possible risks within Panamanian
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
