<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Court Extends Elian's Stay in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals panel barred anyone from
attempting to remove the boy from the country, extending the
injunction issued last week, an Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the appeals judges as saying that they
recognized the government's authority over immigration matters,
but adding that "We fail to see how an injunction in the case
infringes upon the congressional power."
</P>
<P>
The panel was critical of Immigration and Naturalization
Service's handling of the boy's asylum request, saying "It appears
that never have INS officials attempted to interview plaintiff
about his own wishes."
</P>
<P>
"It is not clear that the INS, in finding plaintiff's father to
be the only proper representative, considered all of the relevant
factors, particularly the child's separate and independent
interests in seeking asylum," the judges wrote in a ruling
statement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Attorney General Janet Reno told a regular
briefing that Elian's parents did "a very good job of raising him,
and now it is time for his father to be on with that task."
</P>
<P>
Reno told reporters that the Justice Department will consider
next steps in consultations with President Bill Clinton after the
rule of the appeals court, but she affirmed that the law
enforcement will have to be carried out.
</P>
<P>
"I am dead set and determined to do it the right way, the
safest way, the least violent way, and the soonest way I possibly
can under the law," she added. "We will utilize all law
enforcement options, if appropriate under the 11th Circuit order."
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 near a shipwreck after his
mother and 10 others were killed when their boat capsized in the
sea off Florida and later was sent to his relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
The INS ruled early this year the boy belongs to his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, and should be returned to Cuba while the
Miami relatives insist Elian stay with them in the United States.
The father arrived early this month and has been waiting for
reunion with his son.
</P>
<P>
The court order upheld Wednesday had temporarily blocked anyone
from taking Elian out of the country until it decides whether to
hear the asylum claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
