<HEADLINE> Landslide Causes Over 10 Deaths in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 died and many people
disappeared as a result of the landslide which took place
Wednesday in the town of Quevedo, southwest of the capital, due to
continuous raining in the eastern part of the country, according
with local reports.
</P>
<P>
At 02:00 local time (0700 GMT), the landslide covered many
houses in a neighborhood of Quevedo, after a heavy downpour that
lasted 12 hours and was strong enough to tear down a wall.
</P>
<P>
Many other places around the country had been affected as well
by the rains last February, when winter's strongest raining period
started, said the National Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology.
</P>
<P>
The capital was declared in a state of emergency after
landslide in the south zone left four dead and 25 injured, some 20
houses destroyed and about 180 people evacuated.
</P>
<P>
In Cuenca, a strong thunderstorm, in prior days, killed a
person and left 20 people homeless, while in Portoviejo, eight
houses were flooded by the rains and the overflowing of the rivers
that feed the Poza Honda dam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
