<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Conditionally Backs Minimum Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said on Wednesday that he is not opposed to the idea of a minimum
wage as long as it can be applied to ensure rapid economic growth
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Museveni made the remark when addressing representatives of
employers and workers at the Uganda International Conference
Centre in Kampala, according to a press release from the
President's Office.
</P>
<P>
It is possible to support labor either through the wage policy
or through increased investments that create more jobs and
increase demand for labor, said the president.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said a wage policy can stimulate or discourage rapid
economic growth and affects investments, he added.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the labour representatives to work with the
government to eliminate the main bottlenecks presently hindering
investments which include high interest rates, lack of serviced
industrial land, high transport costs from the sea ports,
slowness in settling commercial disputes, insecurity in some areas
and smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Despite these difficulties, the president said, the government
of the National Resistance Movement has made important strides by
liberalizing the economy, returning the properties of Asians,
establishing a convertible currency and ensuring macro-economic
stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
