<HEADLINE> Ghana Committed to ECOWAS Monetary Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Ghana on Wednesday resolved to
continue to play an active role in the regional monetary
integration despite the financial crisis, Ghana News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Kwamena Ahwoi, Minister of Planning, Regional Economic
Cooperation and Integration, told a meeting in Ghana's capital
Accra that the proposed second single monetary zone for the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) may help the
country rid of the current violent exchange rate fluctuation.
Ghana's currency has devaluated by 80 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, or the first session of the Ministerial
Convergence Council on the Second Monetary Zone for ECOWAS, was
attended by ministers of trade, commerce, energy, transport and
governors of central banks from Ghana, Nigeria, Guinea, Liberia,
The Gambia, Sierra Leone and Mali.
</P>
<P>
The first six countries had resolved to form the second
monetary zone by 2003 as a step toward merging with the CFA (West
African Franc) countries to forge a single monetary area covering
the whole West Africa with a population of some 250 million.
</P>
<P>
Mali, current chairman of ECOWAS, is attending the meeting as
an observer.
</P>
<P>
Lansana Kouyate, Executive Secretary of the ECOWAS, asked the
ministers to examine relevant proposals ahead of the mini-summit
of some ECOWAS members' heads of state which begins on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
