<HEADLINE> Lawyer for Elian's Father Urges Immediate Action for Reunion of Father and Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The lawyer for the father of
Cuban boy Elian Gonzalez said Wednesday that Atlanta's court
decision to extend the custody of the six-year-old shipwreck
survivor in the United States would not weaken the father's claim
for his son and urged the government to immediately reunite them.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing in the order issued today by the 11th Circuit
undermines or weakens this father's legal and moral claim that he
be given immediate custody of his son," Lawyer Gregory Craig said
in a statement at his Washington office.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
panel ruled that no one would be allowed to remove Elian, now
staying in Miami with his distant relatives since his rescue from
a shipwreck last November, from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Craig said the 11th Circuit Court's decision "places the
obligation to act squarely on the shoulders of Attorney General
Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the government did not act immediately to
remove Elian from the custody of his distant great-uncle Lazaro
Gonzalez and return him to his father Juan Miguel Gonzalez, it
would "bear responsibility for the harm that continues to be
inflicted on Juan Miguel's beloved son."
</P>
<P>
The real issue, Craig said, was not whether the boy would leave
the United States, but "the issue has always been whether this
child would be returned to his father," and when they will reunite.
</P>
<P>
"We call upon the United States government to immediate action,
" he said. "It is unconscionable to wait one day longer. To do so
will only cause more harm to Elian."
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Reno told reporters that the Justice
Department would consider next steps in consultations with
President Bill Clinton after the rule of the Circuit Court. She
reaffirmed that the law enforcement would have to be carried out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
