<HEADLINE> Mexico, U.S. Start Border Demarcation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The authorities of Mexico and the
United States began to put demarcation signs in remote areas where
the border line between both countries either does not exist or is
barely perceptible.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was proposed by Mexican Ambassador to the United
States Jesus Reyes Heroles to prevent accidental incursions by
police members from both countries, according to reports reaching
here from El Paso (Texas).
</P>
<P>
The bilateral Water and Limits International Commission's
spokeswoman Sally Spener said that this organism started to put
three signs last week, made of reflecting material to be easily
seen in the night.
</P>
<P>
The signs, one meter high and three meter wide, mounted in
metal posts, say in English towards American territory "Limit of
the United States of America" and in Spanish "Limite de los
Estados Unidos Mexicanos" (Limit of the United States of Mexico),
according to Spener.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total 3,200-kilometer border between Mexico and the
United States, 2,120 kilometers are delimited by the Rio Grande (
Rio Bravo) and 1,080 kilometers by a fence that extends from El
Paso (Texas) to the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
In some desert zones many sections of the border fence are
destroyed. Along the land border, some 275 landmarks -- 1.5 meters
X 3 meters -- delimit both countries' border.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000419.0381 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Council Condemns Deliberate Targeting of Civilians in Armed Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council Wednesday adopted a resolution reaffirming its
strong condemnation of the deliberate targeting of civilians or
other protected persons in a situation of armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council concluded its one-day
open debate on protection of civilians in armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
In the resolution, the council noted that the overwhelming
majority of internally displaced persons and other vulnerable
groups in a situation of armed conflict are civilians and, as such,
are entitled to the protection afforded to civilians under
existing international humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council said that deliberate targeting of
civilian populations, or other protected persons and the
committing of systematic, flagrant and widespread violations of
international humanitarian and human rights law in a situation of
armed conflict may constitute a threat to international peace and
security and, in this regard, the council reaffirmed its readiness
to consider such situations and, where necessary, to adopt
appropriate steps.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its intention to collaborate with
representatives of the relevant regional and subregional
organizations, where appropriate, in order further to improve
opportunities for the resolution of armed conflicts and the
protection of civilians in such conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The council underlined the importance of safe and unimpeded
access of humanitarian personnel to civilians in armed conflicts
and called upon all parties concerned, including neighboring
states, to cooperate fully with the United Nations Humanitarian
Coordinator and U.N. agencies in providing such access.
</P>
<P>
The council urged the parties to a conflict to make special
arrangements to meet the protection and assistance requirements of
women, children and other vulnerable groups.
</P>
<P>
The council emphasized the importance for humanitarian
organizations to uphold the principles of neutrality, impartiality
and humanity in their humanitarian activities.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated its call to all parties concerned,
including non-state parties, to ensure the safety, security and
freedom of movement of United Nations and associated personnel, as
well as personnel of humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
The council affirmed its intention to ensure that peacekeeping
missions are given suitable mandate and adequate resources to
protect civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
