<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stocks Continue To Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading stock markets
closed higher Wednesday owing to strong earnings of several
technology companies and gains for the U.S. Nasdaq composite after
a sluggish start.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 ended trading on a high note as blue-chip
drugs, telecoms and banking stocks turned in a solid pre-Easter
performance to cement their recovery from Monday's six-month lows.
</P>
<P>
Shares of the international fund manager Amvescap led the way
in London, rising 12.7 percent after the company posted a 79
percent increase in first-quarter profit.
</P>
<P>
Among business services firms, Hays rose 8.5 percent and Capita
Group rose 7.3 percent. Cable company Carlton Communications
climbed 6.1 percent and telecom Cable &AMP;Wireless rose 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300, a broad measure of the region's largest
stocks, was up 1.5 percent, with the computer sub-index up more
than 6 percent and information technology stocks rising 5.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt added 20.22 points, also 0.3 percent,
to 7,216.71, led by software company SAP, up 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Germany's financial sector returned to life after several
losing sessions. Dresdner Bank rose 2.8 percent after local media
reports said ABN Amro and an unnamed U.S. bank viewed it as a
potential takeover target.
</P>
<P>
The bourse in Paris ended modestly higher after another
volatile session where a trendless market struggled with
uneasiness about Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 benchmark index ended up 19.02 or 0.31 percent at 6,
166.46 points in a wide 6,237.97-6,120.08. 
</P>
</TEXT>
